{"title_page": "Redthroat", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n| name = Redthroat\n| image = The birds of Australia (16989832911).jpg\n| image_caption = Redthroat at top.\n| genus = Pyrrholaemus\n| species = brunneus\n| authority = [[John Gould|Gould]], 1841\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{cite iucn | authors = [[BirdLife International]] | title = ''Pyrrholaemus brunneus'' | volume = 2016 | page = e.T22704593A93976763 | year = 2016 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2016-3.RLTS.T22704593A93976763.en }}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''redthroat''' (''Pyrrholaemus brunneus'') is a small, mostly ground-dwelling species of [[bird]] in the family [[Acanthizidae]]. It is [[Endemism|endemic]] to Australia, occurring mostly in arid and semi-arid areas containing [[acacia]] and [[Chenopodiaceae|chenopod]] shrublands. The species has a distinctive red throat patch and is able to mimic the calls of numerous other bird species.\n\n== Taxonomy ==\nThe first [[Species description|formal description]] of the redthroat was by the English ornithologist and bird artist, [[John Gould]], in 1841 under the present [[binomial name]] ''Pyrrholaemus brunneus''.<ref>{{ cite journal | last=Gould | first=John | author-link=John Gould | year=1840 | title=''Pyrrholaemus brunneus'' | journal=Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London | volume=Part 8 | page=173 | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/30571612 }} Although bearing the year 1840 on the title page, the volume did not appear until 1841.</ref><ref>{{ cite book | editor1-last=Mayr | editor1-first=Ernst | editor1-link=Ernst Mayr | editor2-last=Cottrell | editor2-first=G. William | year=1986 | title=Check-list of Birds of the World | volume=Volume 11 | publisher=Museum of Comparative Zoology | place=Cambridge, Massachusetts | page=426 | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/14484127 }}</ref> The name of the genus ''Pyrrholaemus'' is from classical Greek ''{{lang|grc-Latn|pyrrhos}}'' meaning 'flame-coloured' or 'red' and ''{{lang|grc-Latn|laimos}}'' for 'throat'. The [[Specific name (zoology)|specific epithet]] ''{{lang|la|brunneus}}'' is [[New Latin|modern Latin]] for 'brown'.<ref name=Helm>{{cite book | last=Jobling | first=James A. | year=2010| title= The Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird Names | url=https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling | publisher=Christopher Helm | location=London | isbn= 978-1-4081-2501-4 | pages=[https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling/page/n79 79], 326 }}</ref> The redthroat is a small [[passerine]] bird within the family [[Acanthizidae]], also known as the Australasian warblers. The Acanthizidae were once regarded as a subfamily within the family [[Pardalote|Pardalotidae]]; although current revisions place the Acanthizidae in their own family, sister to the Pardalotidae.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The taxonomy and species of birds of Australia and its territories|last=Christidas |first=Les|publisher=Royal Australasian Ornithologists Union|year=1994 |isbn=1875122060 |location=|pages=|oclc= 635775426}}</ref> The species most closely related to the redthroat are the [[speckled warbler]] (''Chthonicola sagittata''), which was previously classified in the same genus as the redthroat (''Pyrrholaemus''), and the [[pilotbird]] (''Pycnoptilus floccosus'').<ref name=Gardner>{{Cite journal|last=Gardner |first=Janet|last2=Trueman |first2=John|date=2010 |title=Phylogeny and evolution of the Meliphagoidea, the largest radiation of Australasian songbirds|url= https://publications.csiro.au/rpr/download?pid=csiro:EP10371&dsid=DS2|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|volume=55 |issue=3|pages=1087\u20131102|doi= 10.1016/j.ympev.2010.02.005|pmid=20152917}}</ref> Recent phylogenetic studies have found that this clade of species (''Pyrrholaemus-Chthonicola-Pyncnoptilus'') is sister to the [[Hylacola|heathwrens]] and [[Calamanthus|fieldwrens]] (''Hylacola-Calamanthus'').<ref name=Gardner/>\n\n== Description ==\nA small {{cvt|11|-|12|cm}} shy greyish-brown bird, the redthroat is most often seen swiftly darting through low branches and shrubs or hopping mouse-like on the ground. Only adult males have the distinctive small rusty brown throat patch which gives the species its common name and the absence of which makes the identification of females and juveniles more difficult. The upper part of the head, body, wings, and tail are a dark-brownish grey, particularly dark on the rump and tail. While the underbody is predominantly whitish-grey, with a more whitish belly and pale buff colour blending into the flanks and undertail-coverts. The tail is dark-brownish grey with prominent white patches on the tips of the outer tail feathers, which can be seen during flight and with the tail folded. Fine off-white scalloping is visible on the forehead, with off-white eye rings and lores merging into the lighter underparts of the body. May be confused with some [[Acanthiza|thornbill]] species, which are more compact with a shorter tail than the redthroat. Unlikely to be mistaken for fieldwrens or heathwrens, which have a more strongly upturned tail at rest.<ref name=HANZAB>{{Cite book|title=Handbook of Australian, New Zealand and Antarctic birds. Volume 6: Pardalotes to shrike-thrushes|last=Higgins |first=PJ|last2=Peter |first2=JM |publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2002|isbn=0-19-553244-9|location=Melbourne |pages= |oclc= 772731860}}</ref>\n\nThe melodious call, similar to that of a canary, has sustained warbling and loud cheery notes.<ref name=HANZAB/> In addition to its own calls, the redthroat is able to [[Mimicry|mimic]] the calls of numerous other birds including [[pied butcherbird]]s, [[rufous fieldwren]], [[grey fantail]], [[fairywren]]s, thornbills and has even been known to mimic the non-vocal sound of a [[crested pigeon]] in flight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.xeno-canto.org/species/Pyrrholaemus-brunneus|title=Redthroat (Pyrrholaemus brunneus) :: xeno-canto|website=www.xeno-canto.org|access-date=2017-06-15}}</ref><ref name=HANZAB/> Although both sexes call throughout the year, during the breeding season male calls are more sustained. Species is vocal whilst foraging and will also sing while perched atop shrubs and taller trees.<ref name=HANZAB/>\n\n== Distribution ==\nThe redthroat is endemic to mainland Australia, occurring in all states and territories except the [[Australian Capital Territory|ACT]] and Tasmania. The species is most prevalent in Western Australia and South Australia. It has a widespread but scattered distribution throughout most of South Australia. In Western Australia, the species is not present in the far north or the south-east but is prevalent throughout the mid-latitudes of the state. In the Northern Territory, the species is restricted to the south of the state, around the Simpson Desert and the MacDonnell Ranges. In Queensland the species is restricted to inland south-western regions. In Victoria, the species is restricted to the mallee regions in the north west of the state.<ref name=HANZAB/> In New South Wales the species is only known to occur in the far west, in several core populations including Broken Hill, Tibooburra, Penarie and Nearie Lake Nature Reserve.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.environment.nsw.gov.au/threatenedSpeciesApp/profile.aspx?id=10721|title=Redthroat - profile|last=|first= |date=|website=NSW Government, Office of Environment and Heritage|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe species is thought to be mostly sedentary, with no evidence to suggest seasonal migration. Individuals recaptured after banding have all been found within <10&nbsp;km of the banding site.<ref name=HANZAB/>\n\n== Habitat ==\nThe habitat of the redthroat consists primarily of arid and semi-arid regions of inland Australia, but it also occupies some coastal areas, as well as plains and rangelands. Communities it favours are most often acacia and chenopod shrublands. These communities are usually characterised by an overstory of mulga (''[[Acacia aneura]]''), red mulga (''[[Acacia cyperophylla|A. cyperophylla]]'') or lacewood (''A. shirleyi'') with an understory of saltbush (''[[Atriplex]] sp''.), bluebush (''[[Chenopodium]] sp.)'' or emu bush (''[[Eremophila (plant)|Eremophila]] sp.)''.<ref name=HANZAB/> However, in some areas the species is known to occur in [[Mallee (habit)|mallee]] with a diverse understory, semi-arid woodlands, [[banksia]] and [[Leptospermum|tea tree]] thickets and shrublands with an overstory of [[Callitris glaucophylla|white cypress]].<ref name=\":2\" /> The consistent feature among these habitats appears to be the presence of a complex understory which provides suitable foraging and nesting resources for this shy, mostly ground-dwelling species.\n\n== Diet and foraging behaviour ==\nRedthroats are [[omnivore]]s with a diet consisting of seeds from grasses and shrubs as well as a broad variety of invertebrates such as spiders, molluscs and insects.<ref name=HANZAB/> Observations of redthroat foraging behaviour found that the species predominantly forages at heights of less than 1m (73% of observations) and was not observed foraging at heights greater than 3m.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Morris|first=WJ|last2=Wooler|first2=RD|date=2001|title=The structure and dynamics of an assemblage of small birds in a semi-arid eucalypt woodland in south-western Australia|journal=Emu |volume=101 |pages=7\u201312 |doi=10.1071/MU00062}}</ref> This study found that redthroats feed mostly by pouncing on prey from the ground or [[Gleaning (birds)|gleaning]] in low vegetation, with very few instances of hunting on the wing.<ref name=\":3\" /> Another study of foraging behaviour found that all observations of foraging occurred on the ground (<0.1 m), using a combination of gleaning and probing.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Recher |first=HF|last2=Davis |first2=WD |date=2002 |title=Foraging profile of a Salmon Gum woodland avifauna in Western Australia|url= http://www.rswa.org.au/publications/Journal/85(2)/recher85(2).pdf |journal= Journal of the Royal Society of Western Australia |volume=85 |pages=103\u2013111}}</ref>\n\n== Breeding and nesting ==\nBreeding mostly occurs between June\u2013December with some geographic variation in timing. Little is known about sexual behaviour, although the species appears to breed in pairs. Nests are relatively large for a bird of its size (9\u201314&nbsp;cm), often domed, spherical or domed with a round entrance near the top (2.5\u20134&nbsp;cm). Usually constructed of bark strips and bark fibre, often lined with feathers, fur or soft plant material. Nests are located on or close to the ground among shrubs, grass tussocks, at the base of trees, in fallen logs or in small depressions. Two to four eggs are laid and the female is solely responsible for incubating the eggs. The redthroat and the closely related speckled warbler are the only members of the acanthizids which have a solid coloured chocolate brown egg.<ref name=Gardner/> Furthermore, the redthroat (and the speckled warbler) are the primary host species of some [[brood parasite]]s such as the [[black-eared cuckoo]] and [[fan-tailed cuckoo]] which remove redthroat eggs from the nest and lay their own similar looking eggs.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=hhhRGJNqQhIC&pg=PA244 |title=The Avian Brood Parasites: Deception at the Nest|last=Johnsgard |first=Paul A.|date=1997-11-06 |publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780195354997 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=HANZAB/>\n\n==Conservation status==\nPopulations of redthroats have declined in many areas throughout Australia and the species is subject to many threatening processes. This has warranted its conservation listing in New South Wales and Victoria as follows:\n* The redthroat is listed as '''threatened''' on the Victorian [[Flora and Fauna Guarantee Act (1988)]].<ref>[http://www.dse.vic.gov.au/DSE/nrenpa.nsf/LinkView/EADA0F1874AF9CF24A2567C1001020A388BBA5581CF9D859CA256BB300271BDB Department of Sustainability and Environment, Victoria] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050718182613/http://www.dse.vic.gov.au/DSE/nrenpa.nsf/LinkView/EADA0F1874AF9CF24A2567C1001020A388BBA5581CF9D859CA256BB300271BDB |date=2005-07-18 }}</ref>  Under this Act, an ''Action Statement'' for the recovery and future management of this species has not yet been prepared.<ref>[http://www.dse.vic.gov.au/DSE/nrenpa.nsf/LinkView/617768308BCB666E4A25684E00192281E7A24BB36FF60A144A256DEA00244294 Department of Sustainability and Environment, Victoria] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060911130015/http://www.dse.vic.gov.au/DSE/nrenpa.nsf/LinkView/617768308BCB666E4A25684E00192281E7A24BB36FF60A144A256DEA00244294 |date=2006-09-11 }}</ref>\n* On the 2013 advisory list of threatened vertebrate fauna in Victoria, the redthroat is listed as [[endangered]].<ref name=\"DSE200\">{{cite book|title=Advisory List of Threatened Vertebrate Fauna in Victoria - 2013|publisher=Department of Sustainability and Environment|year=2013 |isbn=978-1-74287-504-0 |location=East Melbourne, Victoria|page=11 |author=Victorian Department of Sustainability and Environment|url= https://www.environment.vic.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0014/50450/Advisory-List-of-Threatened-Vertebrate-Fauna_FINAL-2013.pdf}}</ref>\n* The redthroat is listed at Vulnerable under the NSW Threatened Species Conservation Act (1995)<ref name=\":2\" />\nIn New South Wales, several threatening processes affecting redthroat populations have been formally identified, including the following: \n* Clearing of suitable vegetation communities can cause range contractions and isolate populations.\n* [[Overgrazing]] by feral herbivores particularly goats can cause habitat degradation and prevents habitat regeneration for the species. \n* The infestation of suitable habitat by the noxious environmental weed [[Mesquite]] also impacts habitat values and foraging resources.\n* Given that redthroats are predominantly ground-dwelling and nesting birds, they are also highly susceptible to predation by exotic predators such as [[fox]]es and [[cat]]s. \nAlthough the species is not yet federally listed under the [[Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999]], the threatening processes listed above are present throughout most of the species distribution. The ongoing impacts of land clearing, noxious weeds, introduced herbivore and introduced predators are likely to cause further declines throughout the species range, which may warrant further environmental protection measures.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n* Del Hoyo, J.; Elliot, A. & Christie D. (editors). (2006). Handbook of the Birds of the World. Volume 12: Picathartes to Tits and Chickadees. Lynx Edicions. {{ISBN|978-84-96553-42-2}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1310023}}\n\n[[Category:Pyrrholaemus]]\n[[Category:Endemic birds of Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1841]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n| name = Redthroat\n| image = The birds of Australia (16989832911).jpg\n| image_caption = Redthroat at top.\n| genus = Pyrrholaemus\n| species = brunneus\n| authority = [[John Gould|Gould]], 1841\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name = iucn>{{cite iucn | authors = [[BirdLife International]] | title = ''Pyrrholaemus brunneus'' | volume = 2016 | page = e.T22704593A93976763 | year = 2016 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2016-3.RLTS.T22704593A93976763.en }}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''redthroat''' (''Pyrrholaemus brunneus'') is a small, mostly ground-dwelling species of [[bird]] in the family [[Acanthizidae]]. It is [[Endemism|endemic]] to Australia, occurring mostly in arid and semi-arid areas containing [[acacia]] and [[Chenopodiaceae|chenopod]] shrublands. The species has a distinctive red throat patch and is able to mimic the calls of numerous other bird species.\n\n== Taxonomy ==\nThe first [[Species description|formal description]] of the redthroat was by the English ornithologist and bird artist, [[John Gould]], in 1841 under the present [[binomial name]] ''Pyrrholaemus brunneus''.<ref>{{ cite journal | last=Gould | first=John | author-link=John Gould | year=1840 | title=''Pyrrholaemus brunneus'' | journal=Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London | volume=Part 8 | page=173 | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/30571612 }} Although bearing the year 1840 on the title page, the volume did not appear until 1841.</ref><ref>{{ cite book | editor1-last=Mayr | editor1-first=Ernst | editor1-link=Ernst Mayr | editor2-last=Cottrell | editor2-first=G. William | year=1986 | title=Check-list of Birds of the World | volume=Volume 11 | publisher=Museum of Comparative Zoology | place=Cambridge, Massachusetts | page=426 | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/14484127 }}</ref> The name of the genus ''Pyrrholaemus'' is from classical Greek ''{{lang|grc-Latn|pyrrhos}}'' meaning 'flame-coloured' or 'red' and ''{{lang|grc-Latn|laimos}}'' for 'throat'. The [[Specific name (zoology)|specific epithet]] ''{{lang|la|brunneus}}'' is [[New Latin|modern Latin]] for 'brown'.<ref>{{cite book | last=Jobling | first=James A. | year=2010| title= The Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird Names | url=https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling | publisher=Christopher Helm | location=London | isbn= 978-1-4081-2501-4 | pages=[https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling/page/n79 79], 326 }}</ref> The redthroat is a small [[passerine]] bird within the family [[Acanthizidae]], also known as the Australasian warblers. The Acanthizidae were once regarded as a subfamily within the family [[Pardalote|Pardalotidae]]; although current revisions place the Acanthizidae in their own family, sister to the Pardalotidae.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The taxonomy and species of birds of Australia and its territories|last=Christidas |first=Les|publisher=Royal Australasian Ornithologists Union|year=1994 |isbn=1875122060 |location=|pages=|oclc= 635775426}}</ref> The species most closely related to the redthroat are the [[speckled warbler]] (''Chthonicola sagittata''), which was previously classified in the same genus as the redthroat (''Pyrrholaemus''), and the [[pilotbird]] (''Pycnoptilus floccosus'').<ref name=Gardner>{{Cite journal|last=Gardner |first=Janet|last2=Trueman |first2=John|date=2010 |title=Phylogeny and evolution of the Meliphagoidea, the largest radiation of Australasian songbirds|url= https://publications.csiro.au/rpr/download?pid=csiro:EP10371&dsid=DS2|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|volume=55 |issue=3|pages=1087\u20131102|doi= 10.1016/j.ympev.2010.02.005|pmid=20152917}}</ref> Recent phylogenetic studies have found that this clade of species (''Pyrrholaemus-Chthonicola-Pyncnoptilus'') is sister to the [[Hylacola|heathwrens]] and [[Calamanthus|fieldwrens]] (''Hylacola-Calamanthus'').<ref name=Gardner/>\n\n== Description ==\nA small {{cvt|11|-|12|cm}} shy greyish-brown bird, the redthroat is most often seen swiftly darting through low branches and shrubs or hopping mouse-like on the ground. Only adult males have the distinctive small rusty brown throat patch which gives the species its common name and the absence of which makes the identification of females and juveniles more difficult. The upper part of the head, body, wings, and tail are a dark-brownish grey, particularly dark on the rump and tail. While the underbody is predominantly whitish-grey, with a more whitish belly and pale buff colour blending into the flanks and undertail-coverts. The tail is dark-brownish grey with prominent white patches on the tips of the outer tail feathers, which can be seen during flight and with the tail folded. Fine off-white scalloping is visible on the forehead, with off-white eye rings and lores merging into the lighter underparts of the body. May be confused with some [[Acanthiza|thornbill]] species, which are more compact with a shorter tail than the redthroat. Unlikely to be mistaken for fieldwrens or heathwrens, which have a more strongly upturned tail at rest.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Handbook of Australian, New Zealand and Antarctic birds. Volume 6: Pardalotes to shrike-thrushes|last=Higgins |first=PJ|last2=Peter |first2=JM |publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2002|isbn=0-19-553244-9|location=Melbourne |pages= |oclc= 772731860}}</ref>\n\nThe melodious call, similar to that of a canary, has sustained warbling and loud cheery notes.<ref name=\":1\" /> In addition to its own calls, the redthroat is able to [[Mimicry|mimic]] the calls of numerous other birds including [[pied butcherbird]]s, [[rufous fieldwren]], [[grey fantail]], [[fairywren]]s, thornbills and has even been known to mimic the non-vocal sound of a [[crested pigeon]] in flight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.xeno-canto.org/species/Pyrrholaemus-brunneus|title=Redthroat (Pyrrholaemus brunneus) :: xeno-canto|website=www.xeno-canto.org|access-date=2017-06-15}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> Although both sexes call throughout the year, during the breeding season male calls are more sustained. Species is vocal whilst foraging and will also sing while perched atop shrubs and taller trees.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Distribution ==\nThe redthroat is endemic to mainland Australia, occurring in all states and territories except the [[Australian Capital Territory|ACT]] and Tasmania. The species is most prevalent in Western Australia and South Australia. It has a widespread but scattered distribution throughout most of South Australia. In Western Australia, the species is not present in the far north or the south-east but is prevalent throughout the mid-latitudes of the state. In the Northern Territory, the species is restricted to the south of the state, around the Simpson Desert and the MacDonnell Ranges. In Queensland the species is restricted to inland south-western regions. In Victoria, the species is restricted to the mallee regions in the north west of the state.<ref name=\":1\" /> In New South Wales the species is only known to occur in the far west, in several core populations including Broken Hill, Tibooburra, Penarie and Nearie Lake Nature Reserve.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.environment.nsw.gov.au/threatenedSpeciesApp/profile.aspx?id=10721|title=Redthroat - profile|last=|first= |date=|website=NSW Government, Office of Environment and Heritage|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe species is thought to be mostly sedentary, with no evidence to suggest seasonal migration. Individuals recaptured after banding have all been found within <10&nbsp;km of the banding site.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Habitat ==\nThe habitat of the redthroat consists primarily of arid and semi-arid regions of inland Australia, but it also occupies some coastal areas, as well as plains and rangelands. Communities it favours are most often acacia and chenopod shrublands. These communities are usually characterised by an overstory of mulga (''[[Acacia aneura]]''), red mulga (''[[Acacia cyperophylla|A. cyperophylla]]'') or lacewood (''A. shirleyi'') with an understory of saltbush (''[[Atriplex]] sp''.), bluebush (''[[Chenopodium]] sp.)'' or emu bush (''[[Eremophila (plant)|Eremophila]] sp.)''.<ref name=\":1\" /> However, in some areas the species is known to occur in [[Mallee (habit)|mallee]] with a diverse understory, semi-arid woodlands, [[banksia]] and [[Leptospermum|tea tree]] thickets and shrublands with an overstory of [[Callitris glaucophylla|white cypress]].<ref name=\":2\" /> The consistent feature among these habitats appears to be the presence of a complex understory which provides suitable foraging and nesting resources for this shy, mostly ground-dwelling species.\n\n== Diet and foraging behaviour ==\nRedthroats are [[omnivore]]s with a diet consisting of seeds from grasses and shrubs as well as a broad variety of invertebrates such as spiders, molluscs and insects.<ref name=\":1\" /> Observations of redthroat foraging behaviour found that the species predominantly forages at heights of less than 1m (73% of observations) and was not observed foraging at heights greater than 3m.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Morris|first=WJ|last2=Wooler|first2=RD|date=2001|title=The structure and dynamics of an assemblage of small birds in a semi-arid eucalypt woodland in south-western Australia|journal=Emu |volume=101 |pages=7\u201312 |doi=10.1071/MU00062}}</ref> This study found that redthroats feed mostly by pouncing on prey from the ground or [[Gleaning (birds)|gleaning]] in low vegetation, with very few instances of hunting on the wing.<ref name=\":3\" /> Another study of foraging behaviour found that all observations of foraging occurred on the ground (<0.1 m), using a combination of gleaning and probing.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Recher |first=HF|last2=Davis |first2=WD |date=2002 |title=Foraging profile of a Salmon Gum woodland avifauna in Western Australia|url= http://www.rswa.org.au/publications/Journal/85(2)/recher85(2).pdf |journal= Journal of the Royal Society of Western Australia |volume=85 |pages=103\u2013111}}</ref>\n\n== Breeding and nesting ==\nBreeding mostly occurs between June\u2013December with some geographic variation in timing. Little is known about sexual behaviour, although the species appears to breed in pairs. Nests are relatively large for a bird of its size (9\u201314&nbsp;cm), often domed, spherical or domed with a round entrance near the top (2.5\u20134&nbsp;cm). Usually constructed of bark strips and bark fibre, often lined with feathers, fur or soft plant material. Nests are located on or close to the ground among shrubs, grass tussocks, at the base of trees, in fallen logs or in small depressions. Two to four eggs are laid and the female is solely responsible for incubating the eggs. The redthroat and the closely related speckled warbler are the only members of the acanthizids which have a solid coloured chocolate brown egg.<ref name=Gardner/> Furthermore, the redthroat (and the speckled warbler) are the primary host species of some [[brood parasite]]s such as the [[black-eared cuckoo]] and [[fan-tailed cuckoo]] which remove redthroat eggs from the nest and lay their own similar looking eggs.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=hhhRGJNqQhIC&pg=PA244 |title=The Avian Brood Parasites: Deception at the Nest|last=Johnsgard |first=Paul A.|date=1997-11-06 |publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780195354997 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Conservation status==\nPopulations of redthroats have declined in many areas throughout Australia and the species is subject to many threatening processes. This has warranted its conservation listing in New South Wales and Victoria as follows:\n* The redthroat is listed as '''threatened''' on the Victorian [[Flora and Fauna Guarantee Act (1988)]].<ref>[http://www.dse.vic.gov.au/DSE/nrenpa.nsf/LinkView/EADA0F1874AF9CF24A2567C1001020A388BBA5581CF9D859CA256BB300271BDB Department of Sustainability and Environment, Victoria] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050718182613/http://www.dse.vic.gov.au/DSE/nrenpa.nsf/LinkView/EADA0F1874AF9CF24A2567C1001020A388BBA5581CF9D859CA256BB300271BDB |date=2005-07-18 }}</ref>  Under this Act, an ''Action Statement'' for the recovery and future management of this species has not yet been prepared.<ref>[http://www.dse.vic.gov.au/DSE/nrenpa.nsf/LinkView/617768308BCB666E4A25684E00192281E7A24BB36FF60A144A256DEA00244294 Department of Sustainability and Environment, Victoria] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060911130015/http://www.dse.vic.gov.au/DSE/nrenpa.nsf/LinkView/617768308BCB666E4A25684E00192281E7A24BB36FF60A144A256DEA00244294 |date=2006-09-11 }}</ref>\n* On the 2013 advisory list of threatened vertebrate fauna in Victoria, the redthroat is listed as [[endangered]].<ref name=\"DSE200\">{{cite book|title=Advisory List of Threatened Vertebrate Fauna in Victoria - 2013|publisher=Department of Sustainability and Environment|year=2013 |isbn=978-1-74287-504-0 |location=East Melbourne, Victoria|page=11 |author=Victorian Department of Sustainability and Environment|url= https://www.environment.vic.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0014/50450/Advisory-List-of-Threatened-Vertebrate-Fauna_FINAL-2013.pdf}}</ref>\n* The redthroat is listed at Vulnerable under the NSW Threatened Species Conservation Act (1995)<ref name=\":2\" />\nIn New South Wales, several threatening processes affecting redthroat populations have been formally identified, including the following: \n* Clearing of suitable vegetation communities can cause range contractions and isolate populations.\n* [[Overgrazing]] by feral herbivores particularly goats can cause habitat degradation and prevents habitat regeneration for the species. \n* The infestation of suitable habitat by the noxious environmental weed [[Mesquite]] also impacts habitat values and foraging resources.\n* Given that redthroats are predominantly ground-dwelling and nesting birds, they are also highly susceptible to predation by exotic predators such as [[fox]]es and [[cat]]s. \nAlthough the species is not yet federally listed under the [[Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999]], the threatening processes listed above are present throughout most of the species distribution. The ongoing impacts of land clearing, noxious weeds, introduced herbivore and introduced predators are likely to cause further declines throughout the species range, which may warrant further environmental protection measures.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n* Del Hoyo, J.; Elliot, A. & Christie D. (editors). (2006). Handbook of the Birds of the World. Volume 12: Picathartes to Tits and Chickadees. Lynx Edicions. {{ISBN|978-84-96553-42-2}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1310023}}\n\n[[Category:Pyrrholaemus]]\n[[Category:Endemic birds of Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1841]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "name_user": "Rogermccart", "label": "safe", "comment": "ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Redthroat"}
{"title_page": "Lyc\u00e9e International de Saint-Germain-en-Laye", "text_new": "{{Infobox school\n | name                    = Lyc\u00e9e International de Saint-Germain-en-Laye\n | native_name             = \n | image                   = Slottet vid Lyc\u00e9e International de St-Germain-en-Laye.jpg\n | alt                     = \n | caption                 = \n | motto                   = <!-- or | mottoes = -->\n | motto_translation       = \n | address                 = 2 bis rue du Fer \u00e0 Cheval\n | town                    = [[Saint-Germain-en-Laye]]\n | postcode                = 78100\n | country                 = France\n | coordinates             = {{Coord|48|53|44|N|2|3|40|E|region:FR_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n | pushpin_map             = France \u00cele-de-France#France\n | other_names             = {{Hlist|Lyc\u00e9e International|L.I.}}\n | former_name             = <!-- or | former_names = -->\n | type                    = [[State school|Public]] [[international school]]\n | religious_affiliation   = \n | established             = {{Start date|1952}}\n | founder                 = <!-- or | founders = -->\n | closed                  = \n | authority               = <!-- or | educational_authority = or | local_authority = -->\n | oversight               = <!-- use | oversight_label = to override the default label -->\n | headmaster              = France Bessis\n | staff                   = \n | faculty                 = \n | grades                  = <!-- use | grades_label = to override the default label -->\n | gender                  = [[Mixed-sex education|Co-educational]]\n | age_range               = 4-18\n | enrolment               = \n | medium_of_language      = \n | campus_size             = \n | campus_type             = \n | colours                 = \n | teams                   = <!-- use | teams_label = to override the default label -->\n | accreditation           = <!-- or | accreditations = -->\n | publication             = \n | newspaper               = \n | yearbook                = \n | affiliation             = <!-- or | affiliations = -->\n | website                 = {{URL|www.lycee-international.ac-versailles.fr}}\n | footnotes               = \n}}\n[[File:New Building Lycee International.jpg|thumb|Lyc\u00e9e International interior]]\nThe '''Lyc\u00e9e International de Saint-Germain-en-Laye''' (more commonly, '''Lyc\u00e9e International''' or '''L.I.'''; English: International High School of Saint-Germain-en-Laye) is a [[Education in France|French public school]] located in [[Saint-Germain-en-Laye]], Yvelines, in the western suburbs of Paris, France. Established in 1952 as a school for the children of international personnel working at [[Supreme Headquarters Allied Powers Europe]] (SHAPE) in nearby [[Rocquencourt]], the Lyc\u00e9e International caters to students with international and multilingual backgrounds.<ref name=\"British Section\">\"[https://americansectionorg.finalsite.com/about-us/our-program/our-history An Illustrious History],\" ''The American Section: About Us'', accessed April 12, 2020, [https://americansectionorg.finalsite.com/about-us/our-program/our-history].</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lycee-international-stgermain.com/presentation/histoire-du-lycee-international/|title=Histoire du Lyc\u00e9e International|last=|first=|date=|website=Lyc\u00e9e International|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref> With a typical success rate of 99.9 to 100 percent on the French ''[[baccalaur\u00e9at]]'', the Lyc\u00e9e International consistently ranks among France's top public schools and is considered to be the country's best public international schools.<ref name=\"L'Express\">\"Classement des Lyc\u00e9es,\" ''Le Figaro'', accessed April 12, 2020, [https://classement-lycees.etudiant.lefigaro.fr].</ref><ref>\"Palmares des Lyc\u00e9es,\" ''L'Express'', accessed April 12, 2020, [https://www.lexpress.fr/palmares/lycees/].</ref><ref>\"Classement des Lyc\u00e9es 2020,\" L'Etudiant, accessed April12, 2020, [https://www.letudiant.fr/palmares/classement-lycees.html].</ref>\n\nStudents at the Lyc\u00e9e International must be fluent in one of the languages taught in one of the school's fourteen national sections: American, British, Chinese, Danish, Dutch, German, Italian, Japanese, Norwegian, Polish, Portuguese, Russian, Spanish, and Swedish. However, they are not required to be fluent in French to be admitted, as there is a special one-year ''Fran\u00e7ais Sp\u00e9cial'' language program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lefigaro.fr/actualite-france/2019/03/20/01016-20190320ARTFIG00001-au-lycee-international-de-saint-germain-en-laye-une-ecole-monde-pour-les-eleves-bilingues.php|title=Une Ecole Monde pour les El\u00e8ves Bilingues|last=|first=|date=March 20, 2019|website=Le Figaro|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref> The academic curriculum of the international sections supplements the standard French curriculum with additional courses in literature/language and history/geography, taught in the language of the students' respective national sections, allowing them to pursue the [[Baccalaur\u00e9at#Option Internationale du Baccalaur.C3.A9at|''option internationale du baccalaur\u00e9at'']] (OIB), the international variant of the French ''baccalaur\u00e9at''.\n \nThe school's main campus at 2 bis rue du Fer \u00e0 Cheval ({{coord|48|53|44|N|2|3|40|E}}) in Saint-Germain-en-Laye contains a preschool (''maternelle''), a primary school (''\u00e9cole \u00e9l\u00e9mentaire''), a middle school (''coll\u00e8ge''), and an upper school (''lyc\u00e9e''). Due to the size of the student body, some larger national sections have satellite campuses for primary and middle school grades at other local schools in the area of Saint-Germain-en-Laye.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lycee-international-stgermain.com/les-etablissements-partenaires/|title=Les Etablissements Partenaires|last=|first=|date=|website=Lyc\u00e9e International|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref> All students return to the main campus for their final three (''lyc\u00e9e''-level) years.\n\n== History ==\n\nThe history of the school to date can be described by three distinct phases:\n\n===1951\u20131965===\n\nIn 1951, the then-recently established [[NATO]] (North Atlantic Treaty Organisation), a grouping of 15 countries, created [[Supreme Headquarters Allied Powers Europe]] (SHAPE) with the aim of ensuring peace and security in the North Atlantic region, and promising European members the support of the United States in the event of any future aggression.\n\nSHAPE was installed at [[Rocquencourt]], and [[Saint Germain-en-Laye]] was chosen as the place of residence for the serving officers and their families. The SHAPE Village Project was built in the grounds of the Chateau d'Hennemont to accommodate 1,500 officers and soldiers from 13 nationalities, and their families. SHAPE Supreme Commander General [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]] decided to create a school for the children of the officers, which he hoped would help SHAPE's multi-national families to live and work together in harmony.\n\nThe SHAPE village school opened in January 1952, under the direction of Ren\u00e9 Tallard. By the end of the school year, 400 children were on the register, including 200 French children, half of them inhabitants of the town. Two years later, in 1954, the school was officially renamed the NATO International School (l\u2019Ecole Internationale de l\u2019OTAN).\n\nFunding from SHAPE provided the school with equipment and accommodation, including a new flagship building completed in 1960. From 1961, senior students prepared for the Dipl\u00f4me des Ecoles Internationales and the following year, the school was renamed the [[NATO]] International Lyc\u00e9e (Lyc\u00e9e International de l\u2019OTAN). The founding proviseur, Ren\u00e9 Tallard, retired in 1965.\n\n===1965\u20131989===\n\nNot only did 1965 mark the retirement of the much respected Ren\u00e9 Tallard, it was also the year in which President de Gaulle decided to pull France out of NATO\u2019s military operations. NATO, and SHAPE, were forced to find a new European base, in Belgium, and the Lyc\u00e9e International de l\u2019OTAN lost two thirds of its pupils at a stroke. It was an immediate challenge for the new proviseur, Edgar Scherer. His was the delicate task of working with the remaining two public sections \u2013 the German and the Dutch \u2013 to persuade the educational authorities, both in France and overseas, to rebuild the life of the school which, would from now on need to count on the support of \"economic expatriates\" to replace those of the original military community. \n\nBy 1968, under Scherer\u2019s leadership and direction, the school was building up strength with six sections \u2013 German, Dutch, British, American, Danish and Italian.\n\n===1989\u2013present===\n\nScherer\u2019s successor, Jean-Pierre Maillard, had a different challenge: modernising the infrastructure of a school, which had been expanding again over more than twenty years. Replacing pre-fabricated buildings with more lasting structures was now a priority.\n\nThanks to state funding, the result was a new campus, including a fine new primary building. Under Maillard, other projects advanced too: the development of the network of partner schools, the drafting of a \"projet d\u2019\u00e9tablissement\", the creation of the Japanese section in 1993; the embracing of the Option Internationale du Baccalaur\u00e9at as the final exam for senior Lyc\u00e9e students, and the renovation of the chateau.\n\nIn 1997, Maillard handed the baton on to Patrick Charpeil, who focused attention on the administrative complexities of the school, clarifying the legal basis of the Lyc\u00e9e and its component parts. Charpeil continued to oversee the restoration of the chateau and successfully liaised and lobbied with the supervising educational authorities to advance important projects concerning security, major improvements and maintenance.\n\nYves Lemaire took over the helm in September 2001 until September 2012. The challenges were as stimulating as ever: the final stages of renovation and the future use of the chateau; the pressure for increasing the number of classes at Lyc\u00e9e level; nationwide administration of the OIB; the creation of the Polish section at Coll\u00e8ge and Lyc\u00e9e level (in 2002/3) and the consolidation of the legal status of the school via a new decree.\n\nHis successor, Joel Bianco officially took office as the new proviseur in September 2012. He directed the lyc\u00e9e from 2012 to 2016, integrating the Chinese Section. Isabelle Negral was proviseur from 2016 to 2019. She oversaw a major renovation, which included the creation of new secondary buildings, a new preschool building, and a state-of-the art gymnasium, as well as the renovation of the Agora, which will host the CDI, the Maison des Lyc\u00e9ens, meeting rooms, and a center for the arts. France Bessis became proviseur of the school in 2019. \n\n\n== Academics ==\nThe curriculum at the Lyc\u00e9e International combines the French national curriculum with the curriculum of one of the national sections. French Education National teachers teach subjects to French national standards and the school's foreign teachers \u2013 employed in one of the system\u2019s fourteen national sections \u2013 are given the freedom and responsibility to teach literature, language and history to their own national standards. These additional classes in the national sections provide (on a weekly basis):\n\n*Six hours of language class in the primary school\n*Six hours in the middles school, including four hours of literature/language and two hours of history\n*Eight hours in the upper school, usually divided into four hours of literature/language and four hours of history/geography**\n\n(**American Section students have five hours of literature/language and three hours of history/geography, as do Polish Section students. Japanese Section students have six hours of literature/language and two hours of history/geography. Chinese section students take math courses during section time instead of history.)\n\nSince the French curriculum requires learning at least two foreign language, many students who graduate from the Lyc\u00e9e International are fluent in four languages.\n\nStudents who do not speak French are placed in a French immersion program called ''Fran\u00e7ais Sp\u00e9cial''. After one year, they are expected to be fluent in French and integrate the standard French curriculum along with the rest of the student population.\n\nLyc\u00e9e International students must take the international variation on the ''baccalaur\u00e9at'', called the OIB ([[Baccalaur\u00e9at#Variations on the general baccalaur\u00e9at|Option Internationale du baccalaur\u00e9at]]), in order to take advantage of their language skills.\nBaccalaureat results at the Lyc\u00e9e International de Saint Germain-en-Laye fluctuate between 99% and 100%, and an honors (''mention'') rate which is above 90%. These figures are used to compile rankings by national news outlets. While each news outlet has its own ranking system, in all the Lyc\u00e9e International consistently figures among the top ten in France. \n\nClassement des lyc\u00e9es 2019:\n\n* [https://classement-lycees.etudiant.lefigaro.fr Le Figaro]\n* [https://www.letudiant.fr/palmares/classement-lycees.html L'Etudiant]\n* [https://www.lexpress.fr/palmares/lycees/ L'Express]\n* [http://etudiant.aujourdhui.fr/etudiant/annuaire-lycees/classement/lycees-gt.html Le Parisien]\n* [http://www.linternaute.com/ville/lycee/lycee-international/etablissement-0783549J L'Internaute]\n\n\nEvery year many Lyc\u00e9e International students present the prestigious [[Concours g\u00e9n\u00e9ral|Concours G\u00e9n\u00e9ral]]. It is ranked 4th in the country for the cumulative number of winners. \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+'''Number of [[Concours g\u00e9n\u00e9ral|Concours G\u00e9n\u00e9ral]] laureats'''\n!\n!2006\n!2007\n!2008\n!2009\n!2010\n!2011\n!2012\n!2013\n!2014\n!2015\n!2016\n!2017\n!2018\n!2019\n|-\n|'''Number de laureats'''\n|7\n|5\n|8\n|6\n|6\n|9\n|10\n|7\n|9\n|11\n|8\n|6\n|7\n|6\n|}\n<br />\n== International Sections ==\nThe school has fourteen national sections which are essentially run as schools within the school. Students are taught the relevant national curriculum alongside the standard French curriculum. Foreign teachers in each of the national sections give the students lessons in literature, geography and history (from six to eight hours a week according to the grade) in their native tongue. All other disciplines of the official program are taught in French, by French Ministry of Education teachers.\n\n*[https://www.americansection.org American Section] Est. 1952, approx. 700 students\n:There are some 700 students enrolled in the American Section, at three different campuses, ranging from Pre-K (''MS'') through twelfth grade (''Terminale''). Over 50 nationalities are represented in the American Section student body, though the majority of our students hold both French and American nationalities or are French citizens who spent considerable time abroad in English language schools. The common denominator is that all American Section students speak age-appropriate fluent English and are motivated to learn in a demanding bilingual and bicultural environment.\n:The American Section provides an American educational and cultural experience, allowing students to maintain strong links with their American culture while developing a consciousness as global citizens. It pursues its mission through an American curriculum which culminates in the French Baccalaureate with International Option, as well as through a broad and enriching co-curricular program including such activities as drama, music, community service, sports and student publications.\n:The Ecole Schnapper and the Coll\u00e8ge Marcel Roby, also located in St. Germain en Laye, are American Section partner schools. Approximately 65 students in grades K-5 (CP-CM2) attend the Ecole Schnapper, and 160 students in grades 6-9 (6\u00e8me-3\u00e8me) the Coll\u00e8ge Marcel Roby. Students enrolled in these two schools receive the same American Section education as their peers on the Lyc\u00e9e International campus.\n\n*[https://www.britishsection.fr British Section] Est. 1968, approx. 850 students\n*[https://www.sectionchinoise.fr Chinese Section] Est. 2008, approx. 130 students\n*[http://www.sectiondanoise.dk Danish Section] Est. 1952, approx. 60 student\n*[https://www.sectionnl.fr Dutch Section] Est. 1952, approx. 200 students\n*[http://deutsche-abteilung.de German Section] Est. 1954, approx. 600 students\n*[http://www.sectionitalienne.org Italian Section] Est. 1968, approx. 300 students\n*[https://www.li-sectionjaponaise.org Japanese Section] Est. 1993, approx. 200 students\n** The Japanese [[Ministry of Education, Culture, Sports, Science and Technology]] (MEXT) lists that program in its group of European ''[[hoshuko]]'' (part-time Japanese educational programmes).<ref name=MEXTEuropeHoshuko>\"[http://www.mext.go.jp/a_menu/shotou/clarinet/002/006/001/002/004.htm \u6b27\u5dde\u306e\u88dc\u7fd2\u6388\u696d\u6821\u4e00\u89a7\uff08\u5e73\u621025\u5e744\u670815\u65e5\u73fe\u5728\uff09]\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6PT4aGXC8?url=http://www.mext.go.jp/a_menu/shotou/clarinet/002/006/001/002/004.htm Archive]). [[Ministry of Education, Culture, Sports, Science and Technology]] (MEXT). Retrieved on May 10, 2014.</ref>\n*[https://www.section-norvegienne.com Norwegian Section] Est. 1985, approx. 80 students\n*[http://section-polonaise.fr Polish Section] Est. 1998, approx. 90 students\n*[http://www.sectionportugaise.com Portuguese Section] Est. 1973, approx. 420 students\n*[https://section-russe.com/fr/ Russian Section] Est. 2010, approx. 50 students\n*[https://lycee-international-stgermain.com/section-espagnole/ Spanish Section] Est. 1980, approx. 420 students\n*[https://sectionsuedoise.com/fr/ Swedish Section] Est. 1971, approx. 150 students\n\n<br />\n\n== International Cultural Life ==\nParent associations organize numerous events which bring together the school's fourteen international sections:\n\n* Early September: Welcome Day/Open House;\n* End of November: Holiday Sale including traditional crafts and foods;\n* Late December/early January: Jobs and Studies Fair, with over 200 participants;\n* March: Talent Show for students and parents;\n* Mid May: Tournoi des Etoiles international soccer tournament \n* End May: Lyc\u00e9e en F\u00eate with international food booths, artistic performances and games\n* Early July: OIB Graduation Ceremony\n\nIn addition, each section celebrates numerous events linked to their own culture and history, such as the Scandinavian sections' festival of lights, the Japanese spring celebration, and the American Section's potluck dinner and bingo night. Most sections also have specific theater programs and other extra-curricular activities for students.\n\nThe ''foyer socio-\u00e9ducatif'' (FSE) organizes student concerts (Jazz Band, classical orchestra, a-capella singing, choir) and theater performances.\n\n<br />\n\n== Pictures ==\n<br /><gallery widths=\"250\" heights=\"250\" perrow=\"7\">\nCh\u00e2teau d'Hennemont.JPG|Fa\u00e7ade of the Ch\u00e2teau d'Hennemont\nChapelle du Lyc\u00e9e International de Saint-Germain-en-Laye.JPG|Chapel\nR\u00e9fectoire du Lyc\u00e9e International de Saint-Germain-en-Laye.JPG|Canteen\nAgora du Lyc\u00e9e International de Saint-Germain-en-Laye.JPG|The \"Agora\"\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|France|Schools}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.lycee-international.ac-versailles.fr/}} (in French)\n*[https://americansectionorg.finalsite.com American Section website]\n\n{{Saint-Germain-en-Laye}}\n{{Lyc\u00e9es in Yvelines}}\n{{International schools in Paris}}\n{{Japanese weekend schools in Europe}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lycee International De Saint Germain-En-Laye}}\n[[Category:International schools in \u00cele-de-France]]<!--For elementary and middle-->\n[[Category:Lyc\u00e9es in Yvelines|Saint Germain-en-Laye]]\n[[Category:Secondary schools in France]]<!--Junior high-->\n[[Category:Schools in Yvelines]]\n[[Category:French international schools]]\n[[Category:1952 establishments in France]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox school\n | name                    = Lyc\u00e9e International de Saint-Germain-en-Laye\n | native_name             = \n | image                   = Slottet vid Lyc\u00e9e International de St-Germain-en-Laye.jpg\n | alt                     = \n | caption                 = \n | motto                   = <!-- or | mottoes = -->\n | motto_translation       = \n | address                 = 2 bis rue du Fer \u00e0 Cheval\n | town                    = [[Saint-Germain-en-Laye]]\n | postcode                = 78100\n | country                 = France\n | coordinates             = {{Coord|48|53|44|N|2|3|40|E|region:FR_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n | pushpin_map             = France \u00cele-de-France#France\n | other_names             = {{Hlist|Lyc\u00e9e International|L.I.}}\n | former_name             = <!-- or | former_names = -->\n | type                    = [[State school|Public]] [[international school]]\n | religious_affiliation   = \n | established             = {{Start date|1952}}\n | founder                 = <!-- or | founders = -->\n | closed                  = \n | authority               = <!-- or | educational_authority = or | local_authority = -->\n | oversight               = <!-- use | oversight_label = to override the default label -->\n | headmaster              = France Bessis\n | staff                   = \n | faculty                 = \n | grades                  = <!-- use | grades_label = to override the default label -->\n | gender                  = [[Mixed-sex education|Co-educational]]\n | age_range               = 4-18\n | enrolment               = \n | medium_of_language      = \n | campus_size             = \n | campus_type             = \n | colours                 = \n | teams                   = <!-- use | teams_label = to override the default label -->\n | accreditation           = <!-- or | accreditations = -->\n | publication             = \n | newspaper               = \n | yearbook                = \n | affiliation             = <!-- or | affiliations = -->\n | website                 = {{URL|www.lycee-international.ac-versailles.fr}}\n | footnotes               = \n}}\n[[File:New Building Lycee International.jpg|thumb|Lyc\u00e9e International interior]]\nThe '''Lyc\u00e9e International de Saint-Germain-en-Laye''' (more commonly, '''Lyc\u00e9e International''' or '''L.I.'''; English: International High School of Saint-Germain-en-Laye) is a [[Education in France|French public school]] located in [[Saint-Germain-en-Laye]], Yvelines, in the western suburbs of Paris, France. Established in 1952 as a school for the children of international personnel working at [[Supreme Headquarters Allied Powers Europe]] (SHAPE) in nearby [[Rocquencourt]], the Lyc\u00e9e International caters to students with international and multilingual backgrounds.<ref name=\"British Section\">\"[https://americansectionorg.finalsite.com/about-us/our-program/our-history An Illustrious History],\" ''The American Section: About Us'', accessed April 12, 2020, [https://americansectionorg.finalsite.com/about-us/our-program/our-history].</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lycee-international-stgermain.com/presentation/histoire-du-lycee-international/|title=Histoire du Lyc\u00e9e International|last=|first=|date=|website=Lyc\u00e9e International|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref> With a typical success rate of 99.9 to 100 percent on the French ''[[baccalaur\u00e9at]]'', the Lyc\u00e9e International consistently ranks among France's top public schools and is considered to be the country's best public international school.<ref name=\"L'Express\">\"Classement des Lyc\u00e9es,\" ''Le Figaro'', accessed April 12, 2020, [https://classement-lycees.etudiant.lefigaro.fr].</ref><ref>\"Palmares des Lyc\u00e9es,\" ''L'Express'', accessed April 12, 2020, [https://www.lexpress.fr/palmares/lycees/].</ref><ref>\"Classement des Lyc\u00e9es 2020,\" L'Etudiant, accessed April12, 2020, [https://www.letudiant.fr/palmares/classement-lycees.html].</ref>\n\nStudents at the Lyc\u00e9e International must be fluent in one of the languages taught in one of the school's fourteen national sections: American, British, Chinese, Danish, Dutch, German, Italian, Japanese, Norwegian, Polish, Portuguese, Russian, Spanish, and Swedish. However, they are not required to be fluent in French to be admitted, as there is a special one-year ''Fran\u00e7ais Sp\u00e9cial'' language program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lefigaro.fr/actualite-france/2019/03/20/01016-20190320ARTFIG00001-au-lycee-international-de-saint-germain-en-laye-une-ecole-monde-pour-les-eleves-bilingues.php|title=Une Ecole Monde pour les El\u00e8ves Bilingues|last=|first=|date=March 20, 2019|website=Le Figaro|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref> The academic curriculum of the international sections supplements the standard French curriculum with additional courses in literature/language and history/geography, taught in the language of the students' respective national sections, allowing them to pursue the [[Baccalaur\u00e9at#Option Internationale du Baccalaur.C3.A9at|''option internationale du baccalaur\u00e9at'']] (OIB), the international variant of the French ''baccalaur\u00e9at''.\n \nThe school's main campus at 2 bis rue du Fer \u00e0 Cheval ({{coord|48|53|44|N|2|3|40|E}}) in Saint-Germain-en-Laye contains a preschool (''maternelle''), a primary school (''\u00e9cole \u00e9l\u00e9mentaire''), a middle school (''coll\u00e8ge''), and an upper school (''lyc\u00e9e''). Due to the size of the student body, some larger national sections have satellite campuses for primary and middle school grades at other local schools in the area of Saint-Germain-en-Laye.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lycee-international-stgermain.com/les-etablissements-partenaires/|title=Les Etablissements Partenaires|last=|first=|date=|website=Lyc\u00e9e International|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref> All students return to the main campus for their final three (''lyc\u00e9e''-level) years.\n\n== History ==\n\nThe history of the school to date can be described by three distinct phases:\n\n===1951\u20131965===\n\nIn 1951, the then-recently established [[NATO]] (North Atlantic Treaty Organisation), a grouping of 15 countries, created [[Supreme Headquarters Allied Powers Europe]] (SHAPE) with the aim of ensuring peace and security in the North Atlantic region, and promising European members the support of the United States in the event of any future aggression.\n\nSHAPE was installed at [[Rocquencourt]], and [[Saint Germain-en-Laye]] was chosen as the place of residence for the serving officers and their families. The SHAPE Village Project was built in the grounds of the {{Interlanguage link multi|Ch\u00e2teau d'Hennemont|fr}} to accommodate 1,500 officers and soldiers from 13 nationalities, and their families. SHAPE Supreme Commander General Dwight D. Eisenhower decided to create a school for the children of the officers, which he hoped would help SHAPE's multi-national families to live and work together in harmony.\n\nThe SHAPE village school opened in January 1952, under the direction of [[Ren\u00e9 Tallard]]. By the end of the school year, 400 children were on the register, including 200 French children, half of them inhabitants of the town. Two years later, in 1954, the school was officially renamed the NATO International School (l\u2019Ecole Internationale de l\u2019OTAN).\n\nFunding from SHAPE provided the school with equipment and accommodation, including a new flagship building completed in 1960. From 1961, senior students prepared for the [[Dipl\u00f4me des Ecoles Internationales]] and the following year, the school was renamed the [[NATO]] International Lyc\u00e9e (Lyc\u00e9e International de l\u2019OTAN). The founding proviseur, [[Ren\u00e9 Tallard]], retired in 1965.\n\n===1965\u20131989===\n\nNot only did 1965 mark the retirement of the much respected M Tallard, it was also the year in which President de Gaulle decided to pull France out of NATO\u2019s military operations. NATO, and SHAPE, were forced to find a new European base, in Belgium, and the Lyc\u00e9e International de l\u2019OTAN lost two thirds of its pupils at a stroke. It was an immediate challenge for the new proviseur, [[Edgar Scherer]]. His was the delicate task of working with the remaining two public sections \u2013 the German and the Dutch \u2013 to persuade the educational authorities, both in France and overseas, to rebuild the life of the school which, would from now on need to count on the support of \"economic expatriates\" to replace those of the original military community. \n\nBy 1968, under Scherer\u2019s leadership and direction, the school was building up strength with six sections \u2013 German, Dutch, British, American, Danish and Italian.\n\n===1989\u2013present===\n\nScherer\u2019s successor, [[Jean Pierre Maillard|Jean-Pierre Maillard]], had a different challenge: modernising the infrastructure of a school, which had been expanding again over more than twenty years. Replacing pre-fabricated buildings with more lasting structures was now a priority.\n\nThanks to state funding, the result was a new campus, including a fine new primary building. Under Maillard, other projects advanced too: the development of the network of partner schools, the drafting of a \"projet d\u2019\u00e9tablissement\", the creation of the Japanese section in 1993; the embracing of the Option Internationale du Baccalaur\u00e9at as the final exam for senior Lyc\u00e9e students, and the renovation of the chateau.\n\nIn 1997, Maillard handed the baton on to [[Patrick Charpeil]], who focused attention on the administrative complexities of the school, clarifying the legal basis of the Lyc\u00e9e and its component parts. Charpeil continued to oversee the restoration of the chateau and successfully liaised and lobbied with the supervising educational authorities to advance important projects concerning security, major improvements and maintenance.\n\n[[Yves Lemaire]] took over the helm in September 2001 until September 2012. The challenges were as stimulating as ever: the final stages of renovation and the future use of the chateau; the pressure for increasing the number of classes at Lyc\u00e9e level; nationwide administration of the OIB; the creation of the Polish section at Coll\u00e8ge and Lyc\u00e9e level (in 2002/3) and the consolidation of the legal status of the school via a new decree.\n\nHis successor, Joel Bianco officially took office as the new proviseur in September 2012. He directed the lyc\u00e9e from 2012 to 2016, integrating the Chinese Section. Isabelle Negral was proviseur from 2016 to 2019. She oversaw a major renovation, which included the creation of new secondary buildings, a new preschool building, and a state-of-the art gymnasium, as well as the renovation of the Agora, which will host the CDI, the Maison des Lyc\u00e9ens, meeting rooms, and a center for the arts. France Bessis became proviseur of the school in 2019. \n\n\n== Academics ==\nThe curriculum at the Lyc\u00e9e International combines the French national curriculum with the curriculum of one of the national sections. French Education National teachers teach subjects to French national standards and the school's foreign teachers \u2013 employed in one of the system\u2019s fourteen national sections \u2013 are given the freedom and responsibility to teach literature, language and history to their own national standards. These additional classes in the national sections provide (on a weekly basis):\n\n*Six hours of language class in the primary school\n*Six hours in the middles school, including four hours of literature/language and two hours of history\n*Eight hours in the upper school, usually divided into four hours of literature/language and four hours of history/geography**\n\n(**American Section students have five hours of literature/language and three hours of history/geography, as do Polish Section students. Japanese Section students have six hours of literature/language and two hours of history/geography. Chinese section students take math courses during section time instead of history.)\n\nSince the French curriculum requires learning at least two foreign language, many students who graduate from the Lyc\u00e9e International are fluent in four languages.\n\nStudents who do not speak French are placed in a French immersion program called ''Fran\u00e7ais Sp\u00e9cial''. After one year, they are expected to be fluent in French and integrate the standard French curriculum along with the rest of the student population.\n\nLyc\u00e9e International students must take the international variation on the ''baccalaur\u00e9at'', called the OIB ([[Baccalaur\u00e9at#Variations on the general baccalaur\u00e9at|Option Internationale du baccalaur\u00e9at]]), in order to take advantage of their language skills.\nBaccalaureat results at the Lyc\u00e9e International de Saint Germain-en-Laye fluctuate between 99% and 100%, and an honors (''mention'') rate which is above 90%. These figures are used to compile rankings by national news outlets. While each news outlet has its own ranking system, in all the Lyc\u00e9e International consistently figures among the top ten in France. \n\nClassement des lyc\u00e9es 2019:\n\n* [https://classement-lycees.etudiant.lefigaro.fr Le Figaro]\n* [https://www.letudiant.fr/palmares/classement-lycees.html L'Etudiant]\n* [https://www.lexpress.fr/palmares/lycees/ L'Express]\n* [http://etudiant.aujourdhui.fr/etudiant/annuaire-lycees/classement/lycees-gt.html Le Parisien]\n* [http://www.linternaute.com/ville/lycee/lycee-international/etablissement-0783549J L'Internaute]\n\n\nEvery year many Lyc\u00e9e International students present the prestigious [[Concours g\u00e9n\u00e9ral|Concours G\u00e9n\u00e9ral]]. It is ranked 4th in the country for the cumulative number of winners. \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+'''Number of [[Concours g\u00e9n\u00e9ral|Concours G\u00e9n\u00e9ral]] laureats'''\n!\n!2006\n!2007\n!2008\n!2009\n!2010\n!2011\n!2012\n!2013\n!2014\n!2015\n!2016\n!2017\n!2018\n!2019\n|-\n|'''Number de laureats'''\n|7\n|5\n|8\n|6\n|6\n|9\n|10\n|7\n|9\n|11\n|8\n|6\n|7\n|6\n|}\n<br />\n== International Sections ==\nThe school has fourteen national sections which are essentially run as schools within the school. Students are taught the relevant national curriculum alongside the standard French curriculum. Foreign teachers in each of the national sections give the students lessons in literature, geography and history (from six to eight hours a week according to the grade) in their native tongue. All other disciplines of the official program are taught in French, by French Ministry of Education teachers.\n\n*[https://www.americansection.org American Section] Est. 1952, approx. 700 students\n:There are some 700 students enrolled in the American Section, at three different campuses, ranging from Pre-K (''MS'') through twelfth grade (''Terminale''). Over 50 nationalities are represented in the American Section student body, though the majority of our students hold both French and American nationalities or are French citizens who spent considerable time abroad in English language schools. The common denominator is that all American Section students speak age-appropriate fluent English and are motivated to learn in a demanding bilingual and bicultural environment.\n:The American Section provides an American educational and cultural experience, allowing students to maintain strong links with their American culture while developing a consciousness as global citizens. It pursues its mission through an American curriculum which culminates in the French Baccalaureate with International Option, as well as through a broad and enriching co-curricular program including such activities as drama, music, community service, sports and student publications.\n:The Ecole Schnapper and the Coll\u00e8ge Marcel Roby, also located in St. Germain en Laye, are American Section partner schools. Approximately 65 students in grades K-5 (CP-CM2) attend the Ecole Schnapper, and 160 students in grades 6-9 (6\u00e8me-3\u00e8me) the Coll\u00e8ge Marcel Roby. Students enrolled in these two schools receive the same American Section education as their peers on the Lyc\u00e9e International campus.\n\n*[https://www.britishsection.fr British Section] Est. 1968, approx. 850 students\n*[https://www.sectionchinoise.fr Chinese Section] Est. 2008, approx. 130 students\n*[http://www.sectiondanoise.dk Danish Section] Est. 1952, approx. 60 student\n*[https://www.sectionnl.fr Dutch Section] Est. 1952, approx. 600 students\n*[http://deutsche-abteilung.de German Section] Est. 1954, approx. 200 students\n*[http://www.sectionitalienne.org Italian Section] Est. 1968, approx. 300 students\n*[https://www.li-sectionjaponaise.org Japanese Section] Est. 1993, approx. 200 students\n** The Japanese [[Ministry of Education, Culture, Sports, Science and Technology]] (MEXT) lists that program in its group of European ''[[hoshuko]]'' (part-time Japanese educational programmes).<ref name=MEXTEuropeHoshuko>\"[http://www.mext.go.jp/a_menu/shotou/clarinet/002/006/001/002/004.htm \u6b27\u5dde\u306e\u88dc\u7fd2\u6388\u696d\u6821\u4e00\u89a7\uff08\u5e73\u621025\u5e744\u670815\u65e5\u73fe\u5728\uff09]\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6PT4aGXC8?url=http://www.mext.go.jp/a_menu/shotou/clarinet/002/006/001/002/004.htm Archive]). [[Ministry of Education, Culture, Sports, Science and Technology]] (MEXT). Retrieved on May 10, 2014.</ref>\n*[https://www.section-norvegienne.com Norwegian Section] Est. 1985, approx. 80 students\n*[http://section-polonaise.fr Polish Section] Est. 1998, approx. 90 students\n*[http://www.sectionportugaise.com Portuguese Section] Est. 1973, approx. 420 students\n*[https://section-russe.com/fr/ Russian Section] Est. 2010, approx. 50 students\n*[https://lycee-international-stgermain.com/section-espagnole/ Spanish Section] Est. 1980, approx. 420 students\n*[https://sectionsuedoise.com/fr/ Swedish Section] Est. 1971, approx. 150 students\n\n<br />\n\n== International Cultural Life ==\nParent associations organize numerous events which bring together the school's fourteen international sections:\n\n* Early September: Welcome Day/Open House;\n* End of November: Holiday Sale including traditional crafts and foods;\n* Late December/early January: Jobs and Studies Fair, with over 200 participants;\n* March: Talent Show for students and parents;\n* Mid May: Tournoi des Etoiles international soccer tournament \n* End May: Lyc\u00e9e en F\u00eate with international food booths, artistic performances and games\n* Early July: OIB Graduation Ceremony\n\nIn addition, each section celebrates numerous events linked to their own culture and history, such as the Scandinavian sections' festival of lights, the Japanese spring celebration, and the American Section's potluck dinner and bingo night. Most sections also have specific theater programs and other extra-curricular activities for students.\n\nThe ''foyer socio-\u00e9ducatif'' (FSE) organizes student concerts (Jazz Band, classical orchestra, a-capella singing, choir) and theater performances.\n\n<br />\n\n== Pictures ==\n<br /><gallery widths=\"250\" heights=\"250\" perrow=\"7\">\nCh\u00e2teau d'Hennemont.JPG|Fa\u00e7ade of the Ch\u00e2teau d'Hennemont\nChapelle du Lyc\u00e9e International de Saint-Germain-en-Laye.JPG|Chapel\nR\u00e9fectoire du Lyc\u00e9e International de Saint-Germain-en-Laye.JPG|Canteen\nAgora du Lyc\u00e9e International de Saint-Germain-en-Laye.JPG|The \"Agora\"\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|France|Schools}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.lycee-international.ac-versailles.fr/}} (in French)\n*[https://americansectionorg.finalsite.com American Section website]\n\n{{Saint-Germain-en-Laye}}\n{{Lyc\u00e9es in Yvelines}}\n{{International schools in Paris}}\n{{Japanese weekend schools in Europe}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lycee International De Saint Germain-En-Laye}}\n[[Category:International schools in \u00cele-de-France]]<!--For elementary and middle-->\n[[Category:Lyc\u00e9es in Yvelines|Saint Germain-en-Laye]]\n[[Category:Secondary schools in France]]<!--Junior high-->\n[[Category:Schools in Yvelines]]\n[[Category:French international schools]]\n[[Category:1952 establishments in France]]\n", "name_user": "SniknejTeragram", "label": "safe", "comment": "minor corrections", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lyc%C3%A9e_International_de_Saint-Germain-en-Laye"}
{"title_page": "Proto-Romance Language", "text_new": "'''Proto-Romance''' is the [[Comparative method|comparatively]] [[Linguistic reconstruction|reconstructed]] ancestor of all [[Romance languages|Romance Languages]]. It reflects a late variety of [[Latin]], one of the [[Italic languages|Italic Languages]] in the broader [[Indo-European languages|Indo-European]] family.\n\nExceptionally in the field of [[Comparative linguistics|Comparative Linguistics]], specialists in Proto-Romance have at their disposal an abundant corpus of their [[Proto-language|proto language]] in its written register- that is to say, Latin. This has however had the drawback of leading many scholars to rely excessively on the written record in lieu of reconstructing Proto-Romance proper.<ref>Dworkin (2016), p. 2</ref> \n\nAs conceived in the Dictionnaire \u00c9tymologique Roman, Proto-Romance most closely reflects Latin as spoken around the sixth century AD.<ref>Kramer (2014), p. 295</ref>\n\n== Phonology ==\n\n=== Monophthongs ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!\n![[Front vowel|Front]]\n![[Central vowel|Central]]\n![[Back vowel|Back]]\n|-\n![[Close vowel|Close]]\n|{{IPA link|i}}\n|\n|{{IPA link|u}}\n|-\n![[Near-close vowel|Near-close]]\n|[[Near-close near-front unrounded vowel|\u026a]]\n|\n|[[Near-close back rounded vowel|\u028a]]\n|-\n![[Close-mid vowel|Close-mid]]\n|{{IPA link|e}}\n|\n|{{IPA link|o}}\n|-\n![[Open-mid vowel|Open-mid]]\n|{{IPA link|\u025b}}\n|\n|{{IPA link|\u0254}}\n|-\n![[Open vowel|Open]]\n|\n|{{IPA link|\u00e4|a}}\n|\n|}\n\n* The open-mid vowels /\u025b, \u0254/ merge with /e, o/ in all unstressed contexts.<ref>Xavier (2014), pp. 73\u20136</ref><ref>Ferguson (1976), p. 78</ref>\n\n* A further reduction is observed in intertonic syllables where /i, u/ merge with /\u026a, \u028a/.<ref>Xavier (2014), pp. 78\u201381</ref>\n\n* Vowels are lengthened allophonically in stressed open syllables,<ref>Loporcaro (2015), pp. 25\u201330</ref> although not /\u026a/ or /\u028a/.<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 69</ref>\n\n* /i, u/ become [j, w] between a consonant and following vowel. [j] then triggers [[Palatalization (sound change)|palatalization]], e.g. /basi\u00e1re/ [bas\u02b2\u00e1\u02d0\u027ee].<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 83</ref>\n\n=== Diphthong ===\nOnly one diphthong can be reconstructed for Proto-Romance, namely /aw/. It can be found in both stressed and unstressed positions.<ref>Ferguson (1976), p. 84</ref> Its phonemic status is however debatable, as it could also be simply regarded as a sequence of /a/ and /u/.<ref>Xavier, p. 81</ref>\n\n=== Consonants ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!\n! colspan=\"2\" |Labial\n! colspan=\"2\" |Coronal\n! colspan=\"2\" |Velar\n! colspan=\"2\" |Palatal\n|-\n!Nasal\n|\n|m\n|\n|n\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!Occlusive\n|p\n|b\n|t\n|d\n|k\n|g\n|\n| rowspan=\"2\" |j\n|-\n!Fricative\n|f\n|\u03b2\n|s\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!Labialized\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|k\u02b7\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!Vibrant\n|\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |r\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!Lateral\n|\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |l\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n\n* When palatalized /t, k, n, l/ become [ts\u02b2, c, \u0272, \u028e].<ref name=\"Xavier\" /><ref>Zampaulo (2019), pp. 50, 78, 94</ref>\n* Intervocalic [c, \u0272, \u028e] regularly [[Gemination|geminate]].<ref name=\"Xavier\">Xavier (2014), pp. 92\u2013115</ref> [ts\u02b2] does so only sporadically.<ref>Wilkin (1926), pp. 11\u201314</ref>\n*Words beginning with /sC/ undergo [[Prothesis (linguistics)|prosthesis]], e.g. /st\u00e1re/ [\u026ast\u00e1\u02d0\u027ee], unless preceded by a vowel.<ref>Xavier (2014), pp. 125\u20136</ref><ref>Hall (1976), p. 128</ref>\n* It is debated whether /k\u02b7/ is its own phoneme or merely an allophone of /ku/ before vowels.<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 100</ref>\n* There is some evidence that /f/ could have been bilabial, but a labiodental is still more likely.<ref>Xavier (2016), p. 38</ref>\n* /b, d, g/ fricativize to [\u03b2, \u00f0, \u0263] between vowels or in contact with /r/ and /l/.<ref>Xavier (2016), p. 48</ref>\n* Intervocalic /di, gi/ do not occur, these having previously reduced to /j/.<ref>Zampaulo (2019), p. 87</ref><ref>Xavier (2016), p. 43</ref>\n*The rhotic may have been [\u027e~r], as in Spanish or Catalan.<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 113</ref>\n*Word-initial /j/ underwent fortition to [\u025f].<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 83</ref><ref>Zampaulo (2019), p. 84</ref>\n* /ll/ had a retroflex realization: [\u026d\u026d].<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 115</ref><ref>Zampaulo (2019), p. 164</ref>\n* /gn/ fricativizes to [\u0263n].<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 95</ref><ref>Zampaulo (2019), p. 80</ref>\n\n== Morphology ==\n\n=== Nouns ===\nProto-Romance nouns had three cases: [[Nominative case|nominative]], [[Accusative case|accusative]], and a combined [[Genitive case|genitive]]-[[Dative case|dative]] which was only used in reference to humans.<ref>De Darde & Gaenge (1992), p. 104</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Class\n| rowspan=\"6\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |I\n| rowspan=\"6\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |II\n| rowspan=\"6\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |III f.\n| rowspan=\"6\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |III m.\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Nominative\n|f\u00e9m\u026ana\n|f\u00e9m\u026ane\n|f\u00ed\u028e\u028e\u028as\n|f\u00ed\u028e\u028ei\n|m\u00e1tr\u026as''{{efn|De Dardel hesitates to posit this form, giving ''m\u00e1tre'' as a possible alternative. Likewise ''p\u00e1tr\u026as~p\u00e1tre''.|name=|group=lower-greek}}''\n|m\u00e1tres\n|p\u00e1tr\u026as\n|p\u00e1tri\n|-\n!Accusative\n|f\u00e9m\u026ana\n|f\u00e9m\u026anas\n|f\u00ed\u028e\u028eu''{{efn|For final -u versus -\u028as, see Xavier (2014), p. 78.|name=|group=lower-greek}}''\n|f\u00ed\u028e\u028eos\n|m\u00e1tre\n|m\u00e1tres\n|p\u00e1tre\n|p\u00e1tres\n|-\n!Gen-Dat.\n|f\u00e9m\u026ane\n|fem\u026an\u00f3ru''{{efn|Unlike De Dardel, Hall (1976, p. 18) has -''aru'' as the feminine ending, as it was in Classical Latin. On the next page, however, he admits that the evidence for it is flimsy.|name=|group=lower-greek}}''\n|f\u00ed\u028e\u028eo\n|fi\u028e\u028e\u00f3ru\n|m\u00e1tri\n|matr\u00f3ru\n|p\u00e1tri\n|patr\u00f3ru\n|-\n!Translation\n| colspan=\"2\" |woman\n| colspan=\"2\" |son\n| colspan=\"2\" |mother\n| colspan=\"2\" |father\n|}\n\nSeveral Class III nouns had inflections that differed by syllable count or stress position.<ref>Hall (1983), p. 28</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Number\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n! colspan=\"5\" |singular\n|-\n!Nominative\n|\u0254\u0301mo\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n|p\u00e1stor\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n|s\u0254\u0301ror\n|-\n!Accusative\n|\u0254\u0301m\u026ane\n|past\u00f3re\n|sor\u00f3re\n|-\n!Translation\n|man\n|pastor\n|sister\n|}\nA few Class II nouns were pluralized with -''a'' or ''-ora,'' these originally having been neuter in Classical Latin. Though their singular was masculine, the plural was treated as feminine.<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 23\u20134, 29\u201330.</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Type\n|\n! colspan=\"5\" |I\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n! colspan=\"5\" |II\n|-\n!Number\n|\n!singular\n!plural\n|\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n|\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Noun''{{efn|Forms given in the accusative.|name=|group=lower-greek}}''\n|\n|\u0254\u0301\u03b2u\n|\u0254\u0301\u03b2a\n|\n|braccu\n|bracca\n|t\u025b\u0301mp\u028as\n|t\u025b\u0301mpora\n| rowspan=\"2\" |\n|p\u025b\u0301kt\u028as\n|p\u025b\u0301ktora\n|-\n!Translation\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |egg\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |arm\n| colspan=\"2\" |time\n| colspan=\"2\" |chest\n|}\nThe plural was often reanalyzed as a feminine singular, resulting in gender shifts.<ref>Akire & Rosen (2010), pp. 193\u20134</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!Number\n|\n!singular\n!plural\n|\n!singular\n!plural\n|\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Original noun\n| rowspan=\"2\" |\n|f\u0254\u0301\u028e\u028eu\n|f\u0254\u0301\u028e\u028ea\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n|k\u0254\u0301rnu\n|k\u0254\u0301rna\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n|l\u026a\u0301\u0263nu\n|l\u026a\u0301\u0263na\n|-\n!Fem. variant\n|f\u0254\u0301\u028e\u028ea\n|f\u0254\u0301\u028e\u028eas\n|k\u0254\u0301rna\n|k\u0254\u0301rnas\n|l\u026a\u0301\u0263na\n|l\u026a\u0301\u0263nas\n|-\n!Translation\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |leaf\n| colspan=\"2\" |horn\n| colspan=\"2\" |firewood\n|}\nSuch a trend had already begun in Classical Latin; for example the feminine noun ''opera'' was formed from the plural of neuter ''opus.''\n\n=== Adjectives ===\n\n==== Absolute<ref>Hall (1983), p. 32</ref> ====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Type\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! colspan=\"5\" |I\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |II\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n|\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Gender\n| colspan=\"2\" |feminine\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" |masculine\n| colspan=\"2\" |either\n|-\n!Nominative\n|bl\u00e1nda\n|bl\u00e1nde\n|bl\u00e1nd\u028as\n|bl\u00e1ndi\n|d\u028a\u0301lk\u026as\n|d\u028a\u0301lkes\n|-\n!Accusative\n|bl\u00e1nda\n|bl\u00e1ndas\n|bl\u00e1ndu\n|bl\u00e1ndos\n|d\u028a\u0301lke\n|d\u028a\u0301lkes\n|-\n!Gen-Dat.\n|bl\u00e1nde\n|bland\u00f3ru\n|bl\u00e1ndi\n|bland\u00f3ru\n|d\u028a\u0301lki\n| -\n|-\n!Translation\n| colspan=\"2\" |pleasant\n| colspan=\"2\" |pleasant\n| colspan=\"2\" |sweet\n|}\n\n==== Comparative<ref>Hall (1983), p. 32</ref> ====\nWhile the original Latin ending ''-(i)or'' still existed, it was only used in a limited number of adjectives.<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 119-20</ref><ref>Maltby (2016), p. 340</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Number\n|\n!singular\n!plural\n|\n!singular\n!plural\n|\n!singular\n!plural\n|\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Nominative\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n|m\u025b\u0301\u028e\u028eor\n|me\u028e\u028e\u00f3res\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n|p\u025b\u0301jor\n|pej\u00f3res\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n|m\u00e1jor\n|maj\u00f3res\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n|m\u026a\u0301nor\n|m\u026an\u00f3res\n|-\n!Accusative\n|me\u028e\u028e\u00f3re\n|me\u028e\u028e\u00f3res\n|pej\u00f3re\n|pej\u00f3res\n|maj\u00f3re\n|maj\u00f3res\n|m\u026an\u00f3re\n|m\u026an\u00f3res\n|-\n!Gen-Dat.\n|me\u028e\u028e\u00f3ri\n| -\n|p\u025bj\u00f3ri\n| -\n|maj\u00f3ri\n|  -\n|m\u026an\u00f3ri\n| -\n|-\n!Translation\n| colspan=\"2\" |better\n| colspan=\"2\" |worse\n| colspan=\"2\" |larger\n| colspan=\"2\" |smaller\n|}\nThe typical way to form a comparative was to add either ''pl\u00fas'' or ''m\u00e1is'' (meaning 'more') to an absolute adjective, which had been done sporadically in Classical Latin as well.<ref>Maltby (2016), pp. 340\u20135.</ref>\n\n==== Superlative ====\nNo dedicated ending existed to express the superlative. A variety of alternatives were used instead, such as an intensifying adverb (m\u028a\u0301ltu, b\u025b\u0301ne, etc.) or a comparative.<ref>Bauer (2016), pp. 340, 359</ref>\n\n==== Possessive<ref>Hall (1983), p. 122</ref> ====\n\nShown here in the feminine singular.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!\n!First person\n!Second person\n!Third person\n|-\n!singular\n|m\u025b\u0301a\n|t\u028a\u0301a\n|s\u028a\u0301a\n|-\n!plural\n|n\u0254\u0301stra\n|\u03b2\u0254\u0301stra\n|<nowiki>-</nowiki>\n|}\n\n=== Pronouns ===\n\n==== Personal<ref>De Dardel & W\u00fcest (1993), p. 43</ref><ref name=\"Hall\">Hall (1983), p. 39</ref> ====\nThese are the equivalents of 'you', 'me', etc.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Person\n|\n! colspan=\"2\" |I\n|\n! colspan=\"2\" |II\n|\n! colspan=\"2\" |III f.\n|\n! colspan=\"2\" |III m.\n|-\n!Number\n|\n!singular\n!plural\n|\n!singular\n!plural\n|\n!singular\n!plural\n|\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Nominative\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n|\u025b\u0301o''{{efn|On the cited page, Hall has this as ''ego''. However ''eo'' is found in Hall (1976), p. 216|name=|group=lower-greek}}''\n|n\u00f3s\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n|t\u00fa\n|\u03b2\u00f3s\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n|\u026a\u0301lla\n|\u026a\u0301lle\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n|\u026a\u0301lli\n|\u026a\u0301lli\n|-\n!Accusative\n|m\u00e9, m\u00e9ne\n|n\u00f3s\n|t\u00e9, t\u00e9ne\n|\u03b2\u00f3s\n|\u026a\u0301lla\n|\u026a\u0301llas\n|\u026a\u0301llu\n|\u026a\u0301llos\n|-\n!Gen-Dat.\n|m\u00ed, m\u026a\u0301\u03b2\u026a\n|n\u00f3\u03b2\u026as\n|t\u00ed, t\u026a\u0301\u03b2\u026a\n|\u03b2\u00f3\u03b2\u026as\n|\u026all\u00e9i\n|\u026all\u00f3ru\n|\u026all\u00fai\n|\u026all\u00f3ru\n|}\n\n==== Interrogative<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 42\u201343</ref> ====\nThese are the equivalents of 'who' and 'what'.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Animacy\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |Animate\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |Inanimate\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Nominative\n| colspan=\"2\" |ku\u00ed\n| rowspan=\"2\" |ku\u026a\u0301d\n| rowspan=\"2\" |ku\u025b\u0301\n|-\n!Accusative\n|ku\u025b\u0301ne\n|ku\u025b\u0301\n|-\n!Gen-Dat.\n| colspan=\"2\" |k\u00fai\n| colspan=\"2\" |k\u00fai\n|}\n\n=== Verbs ===\n\nProto Romance verbs belong to three main classes, each of which is characterized by a different [[thematic vowel]]. Their conjugations are built on three stems and involve various combinations of mood, aspect, and tense.<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 47\u201350</ref> Only one chart is shown below; the rest will be explained in a separate article.\n\n==== Present indicative<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 52\u20136</ref> ====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |First person\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |Second person\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |Third person\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Translation\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Class I\n|k\u00e1nto\n|kant\u00e1m\u028as\n|k\u00e1ntas\n|kant\u00e1t\u026as\n|k\u00e1ntat\n|k\u00e1ntant\n|sing\n|-\n!Class II\n|d\u0254\u0301rmo\n|dorm\u00edm\u028as\n|d\u0254\u0301rm\u026as\n|d\u0254rm\u00edt\u026as\n|d\u0254\u0301rm\u026at\n|d\u0254\u0301rment<br>~d\u0254\u0301rm\u028ant\n|sleep\n|-\n!Class III\n|b\u00e1tto\n|batt\u00e9m\u028as\n|b\u00e1ttes\n|batt\u00e9t\u026as\n|b\u00e1ttet\n|b\u00e1ttent\n|beat\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Irregular\n|s\u028a\u0301n\n|s\u028a\u0301m\u028as\n|\u025b\u0301s\n|\u025b\u0301st\u026as~s\u00e9t\u026as~s\u028a\u0301t\u026as\n|\u025b\u0301st\n|s\u028a\u0301nt\n|am/are/is\n|-\n|\u00e1jo\n|a\u03b2\u00e9m\u028as\n|\u00e1s\n|a\u03b2\u00e9t\u026as\n|\u00e1t\n|\u00e1nt~\u00e1unt\n|have/has\n|}\n\n==== Participles<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 122\u20133</ref> ====\nThere were only two: a present active and a preterite passive. They declined like adjectives.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!Present Active\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!Translation\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!Preterite Passive\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!Translation\n|-\n!Class I\n|am\u00e1nte\n|(is) adoring\n|am\u00e1ta\n|(was) adored\n|-\n!Class II\n|fin\u025b\u0301nte\n|(is) finishing\n|fin\u00edta\n|(was) finished\n|-\n!Class III\n|a\u03b2\u025b\u0301nte\n|(is) possessing\n|a\u03b2\u00fata\n|(was) possessed\n|}\n== Relation to written Latin ==\nContrary to the traditional view, Wright argues that there was no distinction between Latin and Romance prior to the ninth century, the former being only a written representation of the latter. For instance in ninth-century Spain <saeculum> was simply the correct way to spell [sjeglo], meaning 'century'. The writer would not have actually said [s\u025bkulum] any more than a modern English speaker would pronounce <knight> as *[kn\u026axt].<ref>Wright (1982), pp. 44\u201350</ref> \n\n[[Ecclesiastical Latin]], in its spoken form, was created later during the [[Carolingian Renaissance]]. The British scholar [[Alcuin]], tasked by [[Charlemagne]] with improving the standards of Latin writing in France, prescribed a pronunciation based on a fairly literal interpretation of Latin spelling. A word such as <viridiarium> 'orchard' now had to be read aloud precisely as it was spelled rather than as [[Old French]] ''vergier.''<ref>Wright (1982), pp. 104\u20137</ref>\n\nThis had the effect of rendering [[Sermon|sermons]] competely unintelligible to the general public, which prompted officials a few years later at the [[Council of Tours]] to order sermons to be rendered ''in rusticam romanam linguam'', 'in everyday roman speech'.<ref>Wright (1982), pp. 118-20</ref> Another issue was that now two types of speech, Romance and Church Latin, had to coexist within one writing system. Within the same century the first attempts were made to devise an orthography specifically for Romance, as can be seen in the [[Oaths of Strasbourg]] and the [[Sequence of Saint Eulalia|Canticle of Saint Eulalia]], both written in France. As the Carolingian Reforms spread to other Romance-speaking areas, local scholars devised orthographies for their own varieties of Romance as well.<ref>Wright (1982), pp. 122\u201332, 143\u20134</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist-lg}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n* {{Cite journal|last=|first=|last2=|date=2014-11-14|editor-last=Buchi|editor-first=\u00c9va|editor2-last=Schweickard|editor2-first=Wolfgang|editor3-last=Gouvert|editor3-first=Joannes|editor4-last=Kramer|title=Dictionnaire \u00c9tymologique Roman (D\u00c9Rom)|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1515/9783110313482|journal=Beihefte zur Zeitschrift f\u00fcr romanische Philologie|volume=|pages=295|doi=10.1515/9783110313482|via=}}\n* {{Cite book|last=|first=|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/963581913|title=Dictionnaire \u00c9tymologique Roman (D\u00c9Rom) 2|date=2016|publisher=De Gruyter|year=2016|isbn=3-11-045361-4|editor-last=Buchi|editor-first=\u00c9va|location=|pages=|oclc=963581913|editor-last2=Gouvert|editor-first2=Xavier}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Loporcaro|first=Michele|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/1107082342|title=Vowel Length From Latin to Romance|date=2015|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=978-0-19-965655-4|location=|pages=25-30|oclc=1107082342}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=Dworkin|first=Steven N.|date=2016-01-01|title=Do Romanists need to reconstruct Proto-Romance?|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1515/zrp-2016-0001|journal=Zeitschrift f\u00fcr romanische Philologie|volume=132|issue=1|pages=2|doi=10.1515/zrp-2016-0001|issn=1865-9063|via=}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Ferguson|first=Thaddeus|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1515/9783110806960|title=A History of the Romance Vowel Systems through Paradigmatic Reconstruction|date=1976-01-31|publisher=De Gruyter|year=|isbn=978-3-11-080696-0|location=Berlin, Boston|pages=78}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Wilkinson, Hugh E.|first=|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/1055897845|title=Notes on the development of -KJ-, -TJ- in Spanish and Portuguese|date=1926|publisher=Aoyama Gakuin University|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=11-14|oclc=1055897845}}\n* {{Citation|last=Zampaulo|first=Andr\u00e9|title=Palatal Sound Change in the Romance languages|date=2019-08-22|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1093/oso/9780198807384.003.0006|work=Palatal Sound Change in the Romance Languages|volume=|pages=150\u2013199|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-880738-4|access-date=2020-04-01}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=De Dardel|first=R.|last2=Gaeng|first2=P. A.|date=1992|title=La Declinaison Nominale du Latin Non Classique: Essai d'une Methode de Synthese|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1515/prbs.1992.4.2.91|journal=Probus|volume=4|issue=2|pages=|doi=10.1515/prbs.1992.4.2.91|issn=0921-4771|via=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Hall, Robert Anderson, 1911-|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/422266905|title=Proto-Romance phonology|date=1976|publisher=Elsevier|isbn=0-444-00183-2|oclc=422266905}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Hall, Robert A. (Robert Anderson), 1911-1997.|first=|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/10773070|title=Proto-Romance Morphology|date=1983|publisher=John Benjamins Pub. Co|year=|isbn=90-272-3522-8|location=|pages=|oclc=10773070}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=De Dardel|first=Robert|last2=W\u00fcest|first2=Jakob|date=1993|title=Les syst\u00e8mes casuels du prototoman|url=https://elibrary.narr.digital/article/99.125005/vox199310025|journal=Vox Romanica|volume=52|issue=1|pages=25-65|issn=0042-899X|via=eLibrary}}\n*Alkire, Ti; Rosen, Rosen (July 2010). ''Romance Languages: A Historical Introduction''. New York: Cambridge University Press. ISBN <bdi>9780521717847</bdi>.\n*{{Cite book|last=Vincent|first=Nigel|title=Early and Late Latin: Continuity or Change?|last2=Adams|first2=J. N.|last3=Maltby|first3=Robert|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2016|isbn=978-1-107-13225-2|location=|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Wright|first=Roger|title=Late Latin and Early Romance in Spain and Carolingian France|publisher=Francis Cairns|year=1982|isbn=0-905205-12-X|location=Liverpool|pages=}}\n[[Category:Latin]]\n", "text_old": "'''Proto-Romance''' is the [[Comparative method|comparatively]] [[Linguistic reconstruction|reconstructed]] ancestor of all [[Romance languages|Romance Languages]]. It reflects a late variety of [[Latin]], one of the [[Italic languages|Italic Languages]] in the broader [[Indo-European languages|Indo-European]] family.\n\nExceptionally in the field of [[Comparative linguistics|Comparative Linguistics]], specialists in Proto-Romance have at their disposal an abundant corpus of their [[Proto-language|proto language]] in its written register- that is to say, Latin. This has however had the drawback of leading many scholars to rely excessively on the written record in lieu of reconstructing Proto-Romance proper.<ref>Dworkin (2016), p. 2</ref> \n\nAs conceived in the Dictionnaire \u00c9tymologique Roman, Proto-Romance most closely reflects Latin as spoken around the sixth century AD.<ref>Kramer (2014), p. 295</ref>\n\n== Phonology ==\n\n=== Monophthongs ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!\n![[Front vowel|Front]]\n![[Central vowel|Central]]\n![[Back vowel|Back]]\n|-\n![[Close vowel|Close]]\n|{{IPA link|i}}\n|\n|{{IPA link|u}}\n|-\n![[Near-close vowel|Near-close]]\n|[[Near-close near-front unrounded vowel|\u026a]]\n|\n|[[Near-close back rounded vowel|\u028a]]\n|-\n![[Close-mid vowel|Close-mid]]\n|{{IPA link|e}}\n|\n|{{IPA link|o}}\n|-\n![[Open-mid vowel|Open-mid]]\n|{{IPA link|\u025b}}\n|\n|{{IPA link|\u0254}}\n|-\n![[Open vowel|Open]]\n|\n|{{IPA link|\u00e4|a}}\n|\n|}\n\n* The open-mid vowels /\u025b, \u0254/ merge with /e, o/ in all unstressed contexts.<ref>Xavier (2014), pp. 73\u20136</ref><ref>Ferguson (1976), p. 78</ref>\n\n* A further reduction is observed in intertonic syllables where /i, u/ merge with /\u026a, \u028a/.<ref>Xavier (2014), pp. 78\u201381</ref>\n\n* Vowels are lengthened allophonically in stressed open syllables,<ref>Loporcaro (2015), pp. 25\u201330</ref> although not /\u026a/ or /\u028a/.<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 69</ref>\n\n* /i, u/ become [j, w] between a consonant and following vowel. [j] then triggers [[Palatalization (sound change)|palatalization]], e.g. /basi\u00e1re/ [bas\u02b2\u00e1\u02d0\u027ee].<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 83</ref>\n\n=== Diphthong ===\nOnly one diphthong can be reconstructed for Proto-Romance, namely /aw/. It can be found in both stressed and unstressed positions.<ref>Ferguson (1976), p. 84</ref> Its phonemic status is however debatable, as it could also be simply regarded as a sequence of /a/ and /u/.<ref>Xavier, p. 81</ref>\n\n=== Consonants ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!\n! colspan=\"2\" |Labial\n! colspan=\"2\" |Coronal\n! colspan=\"2\" |Velar\n! colspan=\"2\" |Palatal\n|-\n!Nasal\n|\n|m\n|\n|n\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!Occlusive\n|p\n|b\n|t\n|d\n|k\n|g\n|\n| rowspan=\"2\" |j\n|-\n!Fricative\n|f\n|\u03b2\n|s\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!Labialized\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|k\u02b7\n|\n|-\n!Vibrant\n|\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |r\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!Lateral\n|\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |l\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n\n* When palatalized /t, k, n, l/ become [ts\u02b2, c, \u0272, \u028e].<ref name=\"Xavier\" /><ref>Zampaulo (2019), pp. 50, 78, 94</ref>\n* Intervocalic [c, \u0272, \u028e] regularly [[Gemination|geminate]].<ref name=\"Xavier\">Xavier (2014), pp. 92\u2013115</ref> [ts\u02b2] does so only sporadically.<ref>Wilkin (1926), pp. 11\u201314</ref>\n*Words beginning with /sC/ undergo [[Prothesis (linguistics)|prosthesis]], e.g. /st\u00e1re/ [\u026ast\u00e1\u02d0\u027ee], unless preceded by a vowel.<ref>Xavier (2014), pp. 125\u20136</ref><ref>Hall (1976), p. 128</ref>\n* It is debated whether /k\u02b7/ is its own phoneme or merely an allophone of /ku/ before vowels.<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 100</ref>\n* There is some evidence that /f/ could have been bilabial, but a labiodental is still more likely.<ref>Xavier (2016), p. 38</ref>\n* /b, d, g/ fricativize to [\u03b2, \u00f0, \u0263] between vowels or in contact with /r/ and /l/.<ref>Xavier (2016), p. 48</ref>\n* Intervocalic /di, gi/ do not occur, these having previously reduced to /j/.<ref>Zampaulo (2019), p. 87</ref><ref>Xavier (2016), p. 43</ref>\n*The rhotic may have been [\u027e~r], as in Spanish or Catalan.<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 113</ref>\n*Word-initial /j/ underwent fortition to [\u025f].<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 83</ref><ref>Zampaulo (2019), p. 84</ref>\n* /ll/ had a retroflex realization: [\u026d\u026d].<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 115</ref><ref>Zampaulo (2019), p. 164</ref>\n* /gn/ fricativizes to [\u0263n].<ref>Xavier (2014), p. 95</ref><ref>Zampaulo (2019), p. 80</ref>\n\n== Morphology ==\n\n=== Nouns ===\nProto-Romance nouns had three cases: [[Nominative case|nominative]], [[Accusative case|accusative]], and a combined [[Genitive case|genitive]]-[[Dative case|dative]] which was only used in reference to humans.<ref>De Darde & Gaenge (1992), p. 104</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Class\n| rowspan=\"6\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |I\n| rowspan=\"6\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |II\n| rowspan=\"6\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |III f.\n| rowspan=\"6\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |III m.\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Nominative\n|f\u00e9m\u026ana\n|f\u00e9m\u026ane\n|f\u00ed\u028e\u028e\u028as\n|f\u00ed\u028e\u028ei\n|m\u00e1tr\u026as''{{efn|De Dardel hesitates to posit this form, giving ''m\u00e1tre'' as a possible alternative. Likewise ''p\u00e1tr\u026as~p\u00e1tre''.|name=|group=lower-greek}}''\n|m\u00e1tres\n|p\u00e1tr\u026as\n|p\u00e1tri\n|-\n!Accusative\n|f\u00e9m\u026ana\n|f\u00e9m\u026anas\n|f\u00ed\u028e\u028eu''{{efn|For final -u versus -\u028as, see Xavier (2014), p. 78.|name=|group=lower-greek}}''\n|f\u00ed\u028e\u028eos\n|m\u00e1tre\n|m\u00e1tres\n|p\u00e1tre\n|p\u00e1tres\n|-\n!Gen-Dat.\n|f\u00e9m\u026ane\n|fem\u026an\u00f3ru''{{efn|Unlike De Dardel, Hall (1976, p. 18) has -''aru'' as the feminine ending, as it was in Classical Latin. On the next page, however, he admits that the evidence for it is flimsy.|name=|group=lower-greek}}''\n|f\u00ed\u028e\u028eo\n|fi\u028e\u028e\u00f3ru\n|m\u00e1tri\n|matr\u00f3ru\n|p\u00e1tri\n|patr\u00f3ru\n|-\n!Translation\n| colspan=\"2\" |woman\n| colspan=\"2\" |son\n| colspan=\"2\" |mother\n| colspan=\"2\" |father\n|}\n\nSeveral Class III nouns had inflections that differed by syllable count or stress position.<ref>Hall (1983), p. 28</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Number\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n! colspan=\"5\" |singular\n|-\n!Nominative\n|\u0254\u0301mo\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n|p\u00e1stor\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n|s\u0254\u0301ror\n|-\n!Accusative\n|\u0254\u0301m\u026ane\n|past\u00f3re\n|sor\u00f3re\n|-\n!Translation\n|man\n|pastor\n|sister\n|}\nA few Class II nouns were pluralized with -''a'' or ''-ora,'' these originally having been neuter in Classical Latin. Though their singular was masculine, the plural was treated as feminine.<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 23\u20134, 29\u201330.</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Type\n|\n! colspan=\"5\" |I\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n! colspan=\"5\" |II\n|-\n!Number\n|\n!singular\n!plural\n|\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n|\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Noun''{{efn|Forms given in the accusative.|name=|group=lower-greek}}''\n|\n|\u0254\u0301\u03b2u\n|\u0254\u0301\u03b2a\n|\n|braccu\n|bracca\n|t\u025b\u0301mp\u028as\n|t\u025b\u0301mpora\n| rowspan=\"2\" |\n|p\u025b\u0301kt\u028as\n|p\u025b\u0301ktora\n|-\n!Translation\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |egg\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |arm\n| colspan=\"2\" |time\n| colspan=\"2\" |chest\n|}\nThe plural was often reanalyzed as a feminine singular, resulting in gender shifts.<ref>Akire & Rosen (2010), pp. 193\u20134</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!Number\n|\n!singular\n!plural\n|\n!singular\n!plural\n|\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Original noun\n| rowspan=\"2\" |\n|f\u0254\u0301\u028e\u028eu\n|f\u0254\u0301\u028e\u028ea\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n|k\u0254\u0301rnu\n|k\u0254\u0301rna\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n|l\u026a\u0301\u0263nu\n|l\u026a\u0301\u0263na\n|-\n!Fem. variant\n|f\u0254\u0301\u028e\u028ea\n|f\u0254\u0301\u028e\u028eas\n|k\u0254\u0301rna\n|k\u0254\u0301rnas\n|l\u026a\u0301\u0263na\n|l\u026a\u0301\u0263nas\n|-\n!Translation\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |leaf\n| colspan=\"2\" |horn\n| colspan=\"2\" |firewood\n|}\nSuch a trend had already begun in Classical Latin; for example the feminine noun ''opera'' was formed from the plural of neuter ''opus.''\n\n=== Adjectives ===\n\n==== Absolute<ref>Hall (1983), p. 32</ref> ====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Type\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! colspan=\"5\" |I\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |II\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n|\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Gender\n| colspan=\"2\" |feminine\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" |masculine\n| colspan=\"2\" |either\n|-\n!Nominative\n|bl\u00e1nda\n|bl\u00e1nde\n|bl\u00e1nd\u028as\n|bl\u00e1ndi\n|d\u028a\u0301lk\u026as\n|d\u028a\u0301lkes\n|-\n!Accusative\n|bl\u00e1nda\n|bl\u00e1ndas\n|bl\u00e1ndu\n|bl\u00e1ndos\n|d\u028a\u0301lke\n|d\u028a\u0301lkes\n|-\n!Gen-Dat.\n|bl\u00e1nde\n|bland\u00f3ru\n|bl\u00e1ndi\n|bland\u00f3ru\n|d\u028a\u0301lki\n| -\n|-\n!Translation\n| colspan=\"2\" |pleasant\n| colspan=\"2\" |pleasant\n| colspan=\"2\" |sweet\n|}\n\n==== Comparative<ref>Hall (1983), p. 32</ref> ====\nWhile the original Latin ending ''-(i)or'' still existed, it was only used in a limited number of adjectives.<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 119-20</ref><ref>Maltby (2016), p. 340</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Number\n|\n!singular\n!plural\n|\n!singular\n!plural\n|\n!singular\n!plural\n|\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Nominative\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n|m\u025b\u0301\u028e\u028eor\n|me\u028e\u028e\u00f3res\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n|p\u025b\u0301jor\n|pej\u00f3res\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n|m\u00e1jor\n|maj\u00f3res\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n|m\u026a\u0301nor\n|m\u026an\u00f3res\n|-\n!Accusative\n|me\u028e\u028e\u00f3re\n|me\u028e\u028e\u00f3res\n|pej\u00f3re\n|pej\u00f3res\n|maj\u00f3re\n|maj\u00f3res\n|m\u026an\u00f3re\n|m\u026an\u00f3res\n|-\n!Gen-Dat.\n|me\u028e\u028e\u00f3ri\n| -\n|p\u025bj\u00f3ri\n| -\n|maj\u00f3ri\n|  -\n|m\u026an\u00f3ri\n| -\n|-\n!Translation\n| colspan=\"2\" |better\n| colspan=\"2\" |worse\n| colspan=\"2\" |larger\n| colspan=\"2\" |smaller\n|}\nThe typical way to form a comparative was to add either ''pl\u00fas'' or ''m\u00e1is'' (meaning 'more') to an absolute adjective, which had been done sporadically in Classical Latin as well.<ref>Maltby (2016), pp. 340\u20135.</ref>\n\n==== Superlative ====\nNo dedicated ending existed to express the superlative. A variety of alternatives were used instead, such as an intensifying adverb (m\u028a\u0301ltu, b\u025b\u0301ne, etc.) or a comparative.<ref>Bauer (2016), pp. 340, 359</ref>\n\n==== Possessive<ref>Hall (1983), p. 122</ref> ====\n\nShown here in the feminine singular.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!\n!First person\n!Second person\n!Third person\n|-\n!singular\n|m\u025b\u0301a\n|t\u028a\u0301a\n|s\u028a\u0301a\n|-\n!plural\n|n\u0254\u0301stra\n|\u03b2\u0254\u0301stra\n|<nowiki>-</nowiki>\n|}\n\n=== Pronouns ===\n\n==== Personal<ref>De Dardel & W\u00fcest (1993), p. 43</ref><ref name=\"Hall\">Hall (1983), p. 39</ref> ====\nThese are the equivalents of 'you', 'me', etc.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Person\n|\n! colspan=\"2\" |I\n|\n! colspan=\"2\" |II\n|\n! colspan=\"2\" |III f.\n|\n! colspan=\"2\" |III m.\n|-\n!Number\n|\n!singular\n!plural\n|\n!singular\n!plural\n|\n!singular\n!plural\n|\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Nominative\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n|\u025b\u0301o''{{efn|On the cited page, Hall has this as ''ego''. However ''eo'' is found in Hall (1976), p. 216|name=|group=lower-greek}}''\n|n\u00f3s\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n|t\u00fa\n|\u03b2\u00f3s\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n|\u026a\u0301lla\n|\u026a\u0301lle\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n|\u026a\u0301lli\n|\u026a\u0301lli\n|-\n!Accusative\n|m\u00e9, m\u00e9ne\n|n\u00f3s\n|t\u00e9, t\u00e9ne\n|\u03b2\u00f3s\n|\u026a\u0301lla\n|\u026a\u0301llas\n|\u026a\u0301llu\n|\u026a\u0301llos\n|-\n!Gen-Dat.\n|m\u00ed, m\u026a\u0301\u03b2\u026a\n|n\u00f3\u03b2\u026as\n|t\u00ed, t\u026a\u0301\u03b2\u026a\n|\u03b2\u00f3\u03b2\u026as\n|\u026all\u00e9i\n|\u026all\u00f3ru\n|\u026all\u00fai\n|\u026all\u00f3ru\n|}\n\n==== Interrogative<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 42\u201343</ref> ====\nThese are the equivalents of 'who' and 'what'.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Animacy\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |Animate\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |Inanimate\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Nominative\n| colspan=\"2\" |ku\u00ed\n| rowspan=\"2\" |ku\u026a\u0301d\n| rowspan=\"2\" |ku\u025b\u0301\n|-\n!Accusative\n|ku\u025b\u0301ne\n|ku\u025b\u0301\n|-\n!Gen-Dat.\n| colspan=\"2\" |k\u00fai\n| colspan=\"2\" |k\u00fai\n|}\n\n=== Verbs ===\n\nProto Romance verbs belong to three main classes, each of which is characterized by a different [[thematic vowel]]. Their conjugations are built on three stems and involve various combinations of mood, aspect, and tense.<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 47\u201350</ref> Only one chart is shown below; the rest will be explained in a separate article.\n\n==== Present indicative<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 52\u20136</ref> ====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |First person\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |Second person\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |Third person\n| rowspan=\"7\" |\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Translation\n|-\n!Number\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n!singular\n!plural\n|-\n!Class I\n|k\u00e1nto\n|kant\u00e1m\u028as\n|k\u00e1ntas\n|kant\u00e1t\u026as\n|k\u00e1ntat\n|k\u00e1ntant\n|sing\n|-\n!Class II\n|d\u0254\u0301rmo\n|dorm\u00edm\u028as\n|d\u0254\u0301rm\u026as\n|d\u0254rm\u00edt\u026as\n|d\u0254\u0301rm\u026at\n|d\u0254\u0301rment<br>~d\u0254\u0301rm\u028ant\n|sleep\n|-\n!Class III\n|b\u00e1tto\n|batt\u00e9m\u028as\n|b\u00e1ttes\n|batt\u00e9t\u026as\n|b\u00e1ttet\n|b\u00e1ttent\n|beat\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Irregular\n|s\u028a\u0301n\n|s\u028a\u0301m\u028as\n|\u025b\u0301s\n|\u025b\u0301st\u026as~s\u00e9t\u026as~s\u028a\u0301t\u026as\n|\u025b\u0301st\n|s\u028a\u0301nt\n|am/are/is\n|-\n|\u00e1jo\n|a\u03b2\u00e9m\u028as\n|\u00e1s\n|a\u03b2\u00e9t\u026as\n|\u00e1t\n|\u00e1nt~\u00e1unt\n|have/has\n|}\n\n==== Participles<ref>Hall (1983), pp. 122\u20133</ref> ====\nThere were only two: a present active and a preterite passive. They declined like adjectives.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!Present Active\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!Translation\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!Preterite Passive\n| rowspan=\"4\" |\n!Translation\n|-\n!Class I\n|am\u00e1nte\n|(is) adoring\n|am\u00e1ta\n|(was) adored\n|-\n!Class II\n|fin\u025b\u0301nte\n|(is) finishing\n|fin\u00edta\n|(was) finished\n|-\n!Class III\n|a\u03b2\u025b\u0301nte\n|(is) possessing\n|a\u03b2\u00fata\n|(was) possessed\n|}\n== Relation to written Latin ==\nContrary to the traditional view, Wright argues that there was no distinction between Latin and Romance prior to the ninth century, the former being only a written representation of the latter. For instance in ninth-century Spain <saeculum> was simply the correct way to spell [sjeglo], meaning 'century'. The writer would not have actually said [s\u025bkulum] any more than a modern English speaker would pronounce <knight> as *[kn\u026axt].<ref>Wright (1982), pp. 44\u201350</ref> \n\n[[Ecclesiastical Latin]], in its spoken form, was created later during the [[Carolingian Renaissance]]. The British scholar [[Alcuin]], tasked by [[Charlemagne]] with improving the standards of Latin writing in France, prescribed a pronunciation based on a fairly literal interpretation of Latin spelling. A word such as <viridiarium> 'orchard' now had to be read aloud precisely as it was spelled rather than as [[Old French]] ''vergier.''<ref>Wright (1982), pp. 104\u20137</ref>\n\nThis had the effect of rendering [[Sermon|sermons]] competely unintelligible to the general public, which prompted officials a few years later at the [[Council of Tours]] to order sermons to be rendered ''in rusticam romanam linguam'', 'in everyday roman speech'.<ref>Wright (1982), pp. 118-20</ref> Another issue was that now two types of speech, Romance and Church Latin, had to coexist within one writing system. Within the same century the first attempts were made to devise an orthography specifically for Romance, as can be seen in the [[Oaths of Strasbourg]] and the [[Sequence of Saint Eulalia|Canticle of Saint Eulalia]], both written in France. As the Carolingian Reforms spread to other Romance-speaking areas, local scholars devised orthographies for their own varieties of Romance as well.<ref>Wright (1982), pp. 122\u201332, 143\u20134</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist-lg}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n* {{Cite journal|last=|first=|last2=|date=2014-11-14|editor-last=Buchi|editor-first=\u00c9va|editor2-last=Schweickard|editor2-first=Wolfgang|editor3-last=Gouvert|editor3-first=Joannes|editor4-last=Kramer|title=Dictionnaire \u00c9tymologique Roman (D\u00c9Rom)|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1515/9783110313482|journal=Beihefte zur Zeitschrift f\u00fcr romanische Philolo